const a = [
  {"id":2836,"text":"The islets of Langerhans are developed in which month of fetal life?","explanation":"The islets of Langerhans, which are the endocrine portions of the pancreas responsible for producing and releasing hormones like insulin and glucagon, start to develop during the **third month** of fetal life.\r\n\r\nDuring fetal development, the pancreas originates from two buds, the dorsal and ventral pancreatic buds. Around the third month, these buds undergo significant growth, branching, and differentiation. The islets of Langerhans emerge as clusters of specialized endocrine cells within the pancreatic tissue.\r\n\r\nThese islets continue to mature and develop throughout fetal life and postnatally. The proper development and function of the islets of Langerhans are crucial for regulating blood glucose levels and maintaining overall glucose homeostasis in the body.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 244.","responses":[{"text":"Second month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fifth month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sixth month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third month","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fourth month","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2856,"text":"Which artery supplies the infundibulum?","explanation":"The **superior hypophyseal artery** supplies the infundibulum of the pituitary gland. The pituitary gland, also known as the hypophysis, is a small endocrine gland located at the base of the brain in a bony cavity called the sella turcica.\r\n\r\nThe superior hypophyseal artery is a branch of the **internal carotid artery** and is responsible for supplying blood to the upper part of the pituitary gland, which includes the infundibulum and the neural stalk that connects the hypothalamus to the pituitary gland. The infundibulum is a funnel-shaped structure that extends from the hypothalamus to the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland (neurohypophysis).","reference":"Superior hypophysial artery - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 17, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/neuroscience/superior-hypophysial-artery","responses":[{"text":"Inferior hypophyseal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basilar artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior hypophyseal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2861,"text":"A second-year MBBS student is given a slide of an endocrine gland that contains round and oval structures lined by cuboidal epithelium. Which of the following is most likely the endocrine gland?","explanation":"The endocrine gland that contains round and oval structures lined by cuboidal epithelium is most likely the **thyroid gland**.\r\n\r\nThe thyroid gland is a bilobed endocrine gland located in the anterior neck. Each lobe of the thyroid gland is composed of numerous spherical structures known as thyroid follicles. These follicles are lined by cuboidal epithelial cells called thyroid follicular cells. The follicular cells are responsible for producing and storing thyroid hormones, mainly thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3).\r\n\r\nThe cuboidal shape of the follicular cells and the presence of the round and oval follicles are characteristic features of the thyroid gland. These hormones play a crucial role in regulating the body's metabolism, growth, and development.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 82, 430.","responses":[{"text":"Adrenal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pituitary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2888,"text":"What shape are the follicular cells of the thyroid gland when they are highly active?","explanation":"When the follicular cells of the thyroid gland are highly active, they exhibit a **columnar** shape.\r\n\r\nThe thyroid gland is responsible for producing thyroid hormones, mainly thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3), which play a vital role in regulating metabolism, growth, and development in the body. The synthesis and secretion of these hormones occur within the thyroid follicles.\r\n\r\nDuring periods of increased hormonal activity, such as in response to thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) from the pituitary gland, the follicular cells become highly active. They undergo morphological changes and become taller and more columnar in shape. This change is often observed during periods of thyroid hormone synthesis and release.\r\n\r\nThe columnar shape of the follicular cells allows for increased surface area, facilitating the uptake of iodine and the synthesis of thyroid hormones within the thyroid follicles.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 430.","responses":[{"text":"Pseudostratified columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Columnar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2891,"text":"What substance transports thyroid hormones in blood?","explanation":"**Correct Answer: Thyroxine-binding globulin**\r\n\r\nThyroid hormones, primarily thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3), are hydrophobic and insoluble in water. Therefore, they require specific transport proteins to circulate in the bloodstream. One of the main transport proteins for thyroid hormones is **thyroxine-binding globulin (TBG)**.\r\n\r\nTBG is a glycoprotein synthesized by the liver and belongs to the family of thyroid hormone-binding proteins. It has a high affinity for T4 and T3, forming stable complexes with these hormones. These complexes protect the hormones from degradation and facilitate their transport through the blood.\r\n\r\nIn the bloodstream, most of the thyroid hormones are bound to TBG (about 70-75%), while the rest are bound to other transport proteins like transthyretin (prealbumin) and albumin. Only a small fraction of thyroid hormones circulate in their free, unbound form. However, it is the free hormones that are biologically active and can enter target cells to exert their effects.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 431.","responses":[{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transaminase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transcortin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroxine-binding globulin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2912,"text":"Which of the following is an accurate and simple parameter, requiring no calculation, to assess central obesity?","explanation":"**Waist circumference** is an accurate and simple parameter that requires no calculation to assess central obesity. Central obesity refers to the excessive accumulation of fat in the abdominal area and is associated with an increased risk of various health conditions, including type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular diseases, and metabolic syndrome.\r\n\r\nTo measure waist circumference, a flexible measuring tape is placed around the waist, just above the hip bones. The measurement is taken at the end of normal expiration, with the tape snug but not compressing the skin.\r\n\r\nCentral obesity, as indicated by an elevated waist circumference, is an essential component of metabolic syndrome, which includes a cluster of risk factors for cardiovascular diseases and type 2 diabetes. It is a simple and valuable screening tool for identifying individuals at higher risk of obesity-related health issues.","reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 700, 744.\r\n\r\n(2) Schunkert H, Markus MRP, Stritzke J, Preedy VR. Waist circumference and cardiovascular risk. Handbook of Anthropometry: Physical Measures of Human Form in Health and Disease. Published 2012. Accessed June 20, 2022. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4419-1788-1_131","responses":[{"text":"Waist circumference","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight-to-height ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood cholesterol levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight measurement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body mass index","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2919,"text":"Craniopharyngioma is a tumor involving Rathke's pouch. Which of the following is developed from Rathke's pouch?","explanation":"Rathke's pouch is an important structure in embryonic development that gives rise to specific portions of the pituitary gland. During early embryonic life, the stomodeum invaginates to form Rathke's pouch, which eventually differentiates into two parts: the **anterior lobe (adenohypophysis)** and the **intermediate lobe** of the pituitary gland.\r\n\r\nThe **posterior lobe (neurohypophysis)** of the pituitary gland, on the other hand, originates from a downward outgrowth of the hypothalamus called the infundibulum.\r\n\r\nCraniopharyngioma is a tumor that typically arises from remnants of Rathke's pouch. It is a benign tumor that can cause various symptoms due to its location near the hypothalamus and pituitary gland. As Rathke's pouch is the origin of the **anterior lobe of the pituitary gland**, craniopharyngiomas can affect hormonal regulation and lead to endocrine disturbances.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 331.","responses":[{"text":"Pineal body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior lobe of pituitary gland","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Entire pituitary gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior lobe of pituitary gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2959,"text":"Which of the following stimulates the release of growth hormone (GH)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 933.","responses":[{"text":"Increased free fatty acid concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin-like growth factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Starvation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2960,"text":"Which of the following hormones causes an increase in plasma protein levels?","explanation":"**Cortisol**, also known as the stress hormone, causes an increase in plasma protein levels through its role in regulating metabolism during stressful situations. When the body is under stress, cortisol is released from the adrenal glands in response to signals from the hypothalamus and pituitary gland. \r\n\r\nCortisol has a catabolic effect on tissues, meaning it promotes the breakdown of protein and the mobilization of amino acids from muscle tissues. These amino acids are then transported to the liver, where they are used for gluconeogenesis, the process of forming glucose from non-carbohydrate sources. \r\n\r\nIn the liver, cortisol also stimulates the synthesis of acute phase proteins, including C-reactive protein, fibrinogen, and serum amyloid A. These proteins play a crucial role in the body's immune response and inflammatory processes. By increasing the production of acute phase proteins, cortisol enhances the body's ability to respond to stress and inflammation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 963.","responses":[{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Androgens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2992,"text":"Which of the following substances is the precursor for all steroid hormones?","explanation":"**Cholesterol** is the precursor for all steroid hormones. It serves as the starting material from which the body synthesizes various steroid hormones, including glucocorticoids, mineralocorticoids, and sex hormones (estrogens, progesterone, and androgens).\r\n\r\nThe biosynthesis of steroid hormones begins with the conversion of cholesterol to **pregnenolone** by the enzyme cytochrome P450 side-chain cleavage enzyme (P450scc). Pregnenolone then serves as the common precursor for the synthesis of other specific steroid hormones. Depending on the tissue and the specific enzymes present, pregnenolone can be converted into different hormones.\r\n\r\nFor example, in the adrenal cortex, pregnenolone is further converted to mineralocorticoids (aldosterone) and glucocorticoids (cortisol). In the gonads (ovaries and testes), it is converted to androgens (testosterone) and estrogens (estradiol).","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 237.","responses":[{"text":"Valine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pregnanediol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pregnenolone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2999,"text":"Which statement is correct regarding insulin's structure?","explanation":"Insulin is a **heterodimeric protein** hormone that consists of two peptide chains linked together by disulfide bonds. It is synthesized as a single-chain precursor called proinsulin, which is then cleaved to form the active insulin molecule.\r\n\r\nThe two peptide chains in insulin are called the A chain and the B chain. The A chain contains 21 amino acids, and the B chain contains 30 amino acids. These two chains are held together by two interchain disulfide bonds, which give insulin its characteristic three-dimensional structure.\r\n\r\nInsulin is produced and secreted by the beta cells of the pancreas in response to elevated blood glucose levels. It plays a crucial role in regulating glucose metabolism by promoting the uptake of glucose into cells and the storage of glucose as glycogen in the liver and muscle tissues.","reference":"(1) Production of a novel heterodimeric two-chain insulin-Fc fusion protein. Accessed June 18, 2022. https://academic.oup.com/peds/article/doi/10.1093/protein/gzaa026/5959880\r\n\r\n(2) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 308.","responses":[{"text":"It is a glycolipid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a steroid hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a heterodimeric protein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is an amino acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a homodimeric protein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3050,"text":"Which of the following is the diagnostic test for acromegaly?","explanation":"Acromegaly is a condition caused by excessive production of growth hormone (GH) in adulthood, usually due to a benign tumor of the pituitary gland. The most commonly used diagnostic test for acromegaly is the **oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT)**.\r\n\r\nDuring the OGTT, the patient is given a standard oral glucose load, and blood samples are taken at regular intervals to measure GH levels. In a person with acromegaly, GH levels fail to suppress appropriately following glucose ingestion. Normally, glucose ingestion should suppress GH secretion. However, in acromegaly, the pituitary tumor continues to release GH, leading to persistent high levels of GH in the blood.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1079.","responses":[{"text":"Insulin levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose tolerance test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Homocysteine levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver function test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin levels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3062,"text":"A 25-year-old male comes to the outpatient department with complaints of intermittent headache and nausea for 4 months. On examination of the eyes, he has slightly impaired vision and diplopia. What is the most appropriate diagnosis for this patient?","explanation":"Based on the patient's clinical presentation, the most appropriate diagnosis for this 25-year-old male is a **pituitary adenoma**. Pituitary adenomas are benign tumors that arise from the cells of the anterior pituitary gland. They can cause various symptoms depending on their size and hormone-secreting capabilities.\r\n\r\nThe intermittent headache and nausea can be attributed to the tumor's mass effect, leading to increased intracranial pressure. The slightly impaired vision and diplopia (double vision) are likely due to compression of the optic chiasm and adjacent structures by the enlarging pituitary adenoma.\r\n\r\nPituitary adenomas can be classified based on the hormones they produce. The most common type is a **prolactin-secreting adenoma** (prolactinoma), which can cause hyperprolactinemia leading to reproductive and menstrual disturbances.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1070.","responses":[{"text":"Pituitary adenoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamic ischemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ophthalmic inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corneal infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinal damage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3083,"text":"What is the embryonic source of pancreatic development?","explanation":"The **pancreatic buds** are outgrowths from the foregut endoderm.\r\n\r\nInitially, two buds are formed: the **dorsal pancreatic bud** and the **ventral pancreatic bud**. The dorsal bud arises from the dorsal wall of the foregut, while the ventral bud arises from the ventral wall, just below the liver. These buds undergo further growth and migration.\r\n\r\nDuring development, the ventral bud rotates and fuses with the dorsal bud. As a result, the main pancreatic duct is formed from the duct of the ventral bud, while the body and tail of the pancreas develop from the dorsal bud. The head of the pancreas forms from both buds.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 244.","responses":[{"text":"Both dorsal and ventral buds","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral bud","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal bud","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic bud","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Annular bud","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3113,"text":"A patient diagnosed with acromegaly typically presents with which of the following?","explanation":"Patients with acromegaly typically present with gradual and insidious development of specific features. These include enlargement of hands and feet, coarsening of facial features, soft tissue swelling, joint pain, excessive sweating, and headaches.\r\n\r\nOne of the key metabolic abnormalities in acromegaly is **insulin resistance**. Despite increased GH promoting lipolysis, protein synthesis, and gluconeogenesis, tissues become less responsive to insulin. This results in impaired glucose uptake, leading to elevated blood glucose levels. The presence of insulin resistance may contribute to the increased risk of diabetes mellitus in patients with acromegaly.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 986.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 335, 345.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased lipolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased gluconeogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin resistance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased protein synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3123,"text":"The inferior parathyroid glands develop from which of the following?","explanation":"The parathyroid glands, which are responsible for regulating calcium levels in the body, develop from the pharyngeal pouches during embryonic development. The superior parathyroid glands arise from the **fourth pharyngeal pouch**, while the **inferior parathyroid glands** develop from the **dorsal wing of the third pharyngeal pouch**.\r\n\r\n**Embryonic Development of Parathyroid Glands:**\r\n1. Superior Parathyroid Glands: Develop from the **fourth pharyngeal pouch**, which also gives rise to the ultimobranchial body, the precursor of the parafollicular (C) cells of the thyroid gland.\r\n2. Inferior Parathyroid Glands: Arise from the **dorsal wing of the third pharyngeal pouch**, along with the thymus, which develops from the ventral wing of the same pouch.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 163.","responses":[{"text":"Ventral 4th pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal 4th pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral 3rd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal 3rd pharyngeal pouch","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal 2nd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3150,"text":"Which one of the following is not a feature of centroacinar cells?","explanation":"The answer **\"They surround the serous acini\" is correct** because centroacinar cells are not located around the serous acini. Instead, they are found at the center of the serous acini, acting as a bridge between the acini and the intercalated ducts. Centroacinar cells are specialized cells that play a critical role in the exocrine function of the pancreas. They are involved in the production of bicarbonate-rich fluid, which helps neutralize the acidic chyme entering the small intestine from the stomach. This alkaline fluid aids in creating an optimal environment for pancreatic enzymes to function and assists in the digestion of nutrients.","reference":"(1) Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 333.\r\n\r\n(2) Young B, O’Dowd G, Woodford P. Wheater’s Functional Histology: A Text and Colour Atlas. 6th ed. Churchill Livingston/Elsevier; 2014: 288.","responses":[{"text":"They surround the serous acini","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"They lack secretory granules and basophilic striations","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They lie inside the serous acini","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are continuous with the epithelium lining the intercalated ducts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are epithelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3173,"text":"Which is the first endocrine gland to develop in an embryo, approximately 24 days after fertilization?","explanation":"The **thyroid gland** is the first endocrine gland to develop in an embryo, approximately 24 days after fertilization. During embryonic development, the thyroid gland originates from an endodermal structure called the **thyroid diverticulum** or **thyroid primordium**. The diverticulum arises from the floor of the primitive pharynx and descends inferiorly to its final location in the neck.\r\n\r\nAround the 24th day of gestation, the thyroid diverticulum begins to appear as an epithelial proliferation in the pharyngeal floor. As development progresses, it elongates and migrates caudally to reach the anterior neck region, where it eventually becomes the thyroid gland. The gland's descent and migration are guided by a connective tissue structure known as the **thyroglossal duct**.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 168.","responses":[{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pituitary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid gland","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathyroid gland","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3209,"text":"A microscopic slide labeled as pancreas revealed the presence of ducts and islets of Langerhans. A duct lined by stratified columnar was also seen. Which type of pancreatic duct is lined by this epithelium?","explanation":"The duct lined by stratified columnar epithelium in the pancreas is the **large excretory duct**, also known as the **main pancreatic duct**. The main pancreatic duct is the largest duct in the pancreas and is responsible for carrying the exocrine secretions produced by the acinar cells to the duodenum, where they aid in digestion.\r\n\r\nThe pancreas has a complex system of ducts that transport the secretions produced by different types of cells. The secretions from the acinar cells, which contain digestive enzymes, flow into the intercalated ducts, then into the **intralobular ducts**, and finally into the interlobular ducts. These smaller ducts ultimately merge to form the main pancreatic duct.\r\n\r\nWhile the intercalated ducts and intralobular ducts are lined by simple cuboidal epithelium, the main pancreatic duct is lined by **stratified columnar epithelium**, which allows for more efficient transport of secretions due to its larger size and capacity.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 196.","responses":[{"text":"Interlobular duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intralobular duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Striated duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large excretory duct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercalated duct","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3216,"text":"Insulin is released from vesicles of beta cells due to the opening of which channels?","explanation":"Insulin release from beta cells of the pancreas is triggered by the opening of **Ca2+ channels** in response to an increase in blood glucose levels. The process of insulin secretion involves a complex interplay of events known as the **glucose-induced insulin secretion pathway**.\r\n\r\nWhen blood glucose levels rise, glucose enters the beta cells through glucose transporters (GLUT2). The metabolism of glucose leads to the production of ATP. The increased ATP levels result in the closure of ATP-sensitive K+ channels (KATP channels), which causes the membrane potential to depolarize. This depolarization subsequently leads to the opening of voltage-gated Ca2+ channels.\r\n\r\nThe influx of Ca2+ into the beta cells triggers the exocytosis of insulin-containing vesicles (granules) and the release of insulin into the bloodstream. The elevated insulin levels facilitate the uptake of glucose by peripheral tissues, thereby reducing blood glucose levels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 979.","responses":[{"text":"K+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aqua channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mg+2 channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca+2 channels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3230,"text":"Hyperparathyroidism leads to a decrease in plasma levels of which of these?","explanation":"Hyperparathyroidism leads to an increase in plasma levels of calcium (hypercalcemia) and a decrease in plasma levels of **phosphate** (hypophosphatemia).\r\n\r\nIn hyperparathyroidism, the excessive secretion of parathyroid hormone (PTH) from the parathyroid glands causes increased reabsorption of calcium from bones, increased absorption of calcium from the intestines, and decreased excretion of calcium by the kidneys. As a result, the calcium levels in the blood rise.\r\n\r\nAt the same time, PTH also affects the handling of phosphate in the kidneys, leading to increased excretion of phosphate in the urine. This results in a decrease in plasma levels of phosphate.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 165.","responses":[{"text":"Calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3240,"text":"Which of the following is a characteristic of hyperthyroidism?","explanation":"One of the key characteristics of hyperthyroidism is an **increased basal metabolic rate (BMR).** Thyroid hormones, specifically triiodothyronine (T3) and thyroxine (T4), play a critical role in regulating metabolism, and an excess of these hormones results in an accelerated BMR. This increased metabolic rate can lead to weight loss despite increased appetite, which is contrary to increased body weight.\r\n\r\nHyperthyroidism is also associated with tachycardia (increased heart rate) rather than bradycardia, as the excess thyroid hormones can directly affect the heart and cardiovascular system. Patients may also experience heat intolerance, increased sweating, and sensitivity to warm temperatures, which is opposite to intolerance to cold.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1076.","responses":[{"text":"Bradycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intolerance to cold","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased sweating","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased basal metabolic rate (BMR)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased body weight","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3261,"text":"A second-year medical student, while examining the hypophysis cerebri, noticed some\r\nneurons connecting the hypothalamus to the posterior pituitary. Which of the following nuclei of the hypothalamus are connected to the posterior pituitary gland?","explanation":"The nuclei of the hypothalamus that are connected to the posterior pituitary gland are the **supraoptic nucleus** and the **paraventricular nucleus**.\r\n\r\nThe supraoptic nucleus synthesizes and releases antidiuretic hormone (ADH), also known as vasopressin. ADH is responsible for regulating water balance and preventing excessive water loss in the body. When ADH is released into the bloodstream, it acts on the kidneys, promoting water reabsorption, and reducing urine output.\r\n\r\nThe paraventricular nucleus synthesizes and releases oxytocin. Oxytocin plays a crucial role in uterine contractions during labor and delivery and is also involved in milk ejection during breastfeeding.\r\n\r\nBoth ADH and oxytocin are synthesized in the cell bodies of neurons located in the supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei of the hypothalamus. These neurons send their axons down the hypothalamic-hypophyseal tract to the posterior pituitary gland, where the hormones are stored and later released into the bloodstream when needed.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 930.","responses":[{"text":"Supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraoptic and preoptic nuclei","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventromedial and preoptic nuclei","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraoptic and suprachiasmatic nuclei","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraventricular and preoptic nuclei","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3295,"text":"What are the number of amino acids in growth hormone?","explanation":"The **number of amino acids in growth hormone** is **191**.\r\n\r\nGrowth hormone, also known as somatotropin, is a peptide hormone secreted by the anterior pituitary gland. It plays a crucial role in promoting growth, regulating metabolism, and influencing various physiological processes. The structure of growth hormone consists of a single polypeptide chain containing 191 amino acids.\r\n\r\nThe secretion of growth hormone is regulated by the hypothalamus through the release of growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH) and somatostatin. GHRH stimulates the synthesis and secretion of growth hormone, while somatostatin inhibits its release.","reference":"Rodwell VW, Bender DA, Botham KM, Kennelly PJ, Weil PA. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 1186.","responses":[{"text":"230","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"89","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"191","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"51","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3299,"text":"Somatostatin decreases which of the following?","explanation":"**Somatostatin decreases insulin and glucagon secretion**.\r\n\r\nSomatostatin, also known as growth hormone-inhibiting hormone (GHIH), is a peptide hormone produced by the delta cells of the pancreas and certain neurons in the hypothalamus. It has inhibitory effects on the endocrine system and is involved in regulating various hormonal secretions.\r\n\r\nIn the pancreas, somatostatin acts as a paracrine and inhibits the secretion of both insulin and glucagon from the pancreatic beta and alpha cells, respectively. It acts on these cells' receptors, leading to decreased cAMP production and subsequent inhibition of hormone release.\r\n\r\nThe inhibitory effect of somatostatin on insulin and glucagon helps to maintain glucose homeostasis by reducing the release of insulin when blood glucose levels are low and inhibiting glucagon secretion when blood glucose levels are high.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 983.","responses":[{"text":"Cortisol only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin and glucagon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol and insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin only","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3322,"text":"Which of the following types of cells are majorly placed centrally in the pancreas?","explanation":"The pancreas is a gland located in the abdomen, and it plays a crucial role in the regulation of blood glucose levels. It contains various types of cells, each responsible for the secretion of specific hormones. The two major types of cells found in the pancreas are alpha cells and beta cells.\r\n\r\n1. **Alpha cells:** These cells are primarily located in the periphery of the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. They secrete the hormone glucagon, which helps raise blood glucose levels by promoting the breakdown of glycogen in the liver and the release of glucose into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\n2. **Beta cells:** These cells are centrally placed within the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. They are responsible for producing and releasing the hormone insulin. Insulin plays a key role in lowering blood glucose levels by facilitating the uptake of glucose by cells, especially in muscles and adipose tissue.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 427.","responses":[{"text":"Delta cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"PP cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3328,"text":"Which of the following enzymes is needed to convert norepinephrine to epinephrine?","explanation":"The biosynthesis of epinephrine (adrenaline) from norepinephrine occurs in the adrenal medulla. The conversion is catalyzed by the enzyme **Phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase (PNMT)**, which transfers a methyl group from S-adenosylmethionine to norepinephrine to form epinephrine.\r\n\r\nThe biosynthetic pathway for the synthesis of epinephrine is as follows:\r\n1. **Tyrosine Hydroxylase:** Converts the amino acid tyrosine to L-DOPA (dihydroxyphenylalanine).\r\n2. **DOPA Decarboxylase:** Converts L-DOPA to dopamine.\r\n3. **Dopamine Beta-Hydroxylase:** Converts dopamine to norepinephrine.\r\n4. **Phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase (PNMT):** Converts norepinephrine to epinephrine.","reference":"Rodwell VW, Bender DA, Botham KM, Kennelly PJ, Weil PA. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 739.","responses":[{"text":"Monoamine oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Catechol-O-methyltransferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine hydroxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DOPA hydroxylase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3338,"text":"What differentiates the pancreas from the parotid gland?","explanation":"The key difference that sets the pancreas apart from the parotid gland is the **presence of centroacinar cells and absence of striated ducts** in the pancreas.\r\n\r\n1. **Centroacinar cells**: These are specialized cells found in the **center of acini** (clusters of secretory cells) in the pancreas. They play an essential role in the production of pancreatic enzymes. These enzymes are initially synthesized in the rough endoplasmic reticulum of acinar cells and are then transported through the centroacinar cells into the pancreatic duct system.\r\n\r\n2. **Striated ducts**: These are a distinctive feature of the parotid gland. Striated ducts have extensive infoldings of the basal cell membrane, which gives them a \"striated\" appearance. They are involved in modifying the primary saliva by reabsorbing sodium and chloride ions and secreting potassium and bicarbonate ions.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 333.","responses":[{"text":"Secretory cells arranged in a circle around a central duct in the pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of centroacinar cells and absence of striated ducts in the pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of striated ducts in the pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous acini are present in the parotid, not in the pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Compound glands are present in the pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3383,"text":"Which of the following lies anterior to the left adrenal gland?","explanation":"**The pancreas lies anterior to the left adrenal gland.**\r\n\r\nThe pancreas is a dual-function organ with both endocrine and exocrine functions. It is located in the upper abdomen, behind the stomach and in front of the spine. The left adrenal gland is situated on top of the left kidney. Since the pancreas extends across the midline, the tail of the pancreas lies anterior to the left adrenal gland.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the diaphragm is a dome-shaped muscle that separates the thoracic and abdominal cavities, and it lies superior to the left adrenal gland. The spleen is located on the left side of the abdomen, posterior to the stomach and anterior to the left kidney and adrenal gland. The liver is mainly situated on the right side of the abdomen, although a small portion, called the left lobe, extends across the midline and may be adjacent to the left adrenal gland.","reference":"Bashir O. Adrenal gland | radiology reference article | radiopaedia. Org. Radiopaedia. Accessed June 21, 2022. https://radiopaedia.org/articles/adrenal-gland","responses":[{"text":"Pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diaphragm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of them","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3428,"text":"Which of the following is correct about the pancreatic duct?","explanation":"The pancreatic duct, also known as the duct of Wirsung, is a major duct of the pancreas responsible for carrying digestive enzymes and bicarbonate from the pancreas to the duodenum. It begins at the **tail of the pancreas** and runs longitudinally through the pancreas, collecting tributaries from smaller ducts along its course.\r\n\r\nNear the head of the pancreas, the main pancreatic duct usually merges with the common bile duct, forming the hepatopancreatic ampulla (Ampulla of Vater). The ampulla then opens into the duodenum at the major duodenal papilla, which is located on the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 489.","responses":[{"text":"Starts from the neck of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Starts from head and neck of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Starts from the tail of pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Starts from the head of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opens in duodenum at minor duodenal papilla","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3461,"text":"A newborn was diagnosed with multiple congenital anomalies and was having seizures right after it was born with a glucose level of 19 mg/dl. What would be the disease the mother is suffering from to cause these defects in the child?","explanation":"The most likely disease the mother is suffering from, which could cause multiple congenital anomalies and low glucose levels in the newborn, is **gestational diabetes**.\r\n\r\nGestational diabetes is a type of diabetes that develops during pregnancy. It occurs when the mother's body cannot produce enough insulin to regulate blood sugar effectively. High blood sugar levels in the mother can cross the placenta and affect the developing fetus, leading to various congenital anomalies.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the mother's elevated blood sugar levels may have resulted in impaired fetal development, leading to the multiple congenital anomalies observed in the newborn. Additionally, the baby's pancreas would have been exposed to high levels of glucose during gestation, causing an increased insulin response. After birth, when the baby is no longer receiving glucose from the mother, this exaggerated insulin response could result in hypoglycemia, as evidenced by the low glucose level of 19 mg/dl and the occurrence of seizures.","reference":"(1) Abramowski A, Ward R, Hamdan AH. Neonatal hypoglycemia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537105/\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Şimşek DG, Ecevit A, Hatipoğlu N, et al. Neonatal Hyperglycemia, which threshold value, diagnostic approach and treatment?: Turkish Neonatal and Pediatric Endocrinology and Diabetes Societies consensus report. Turkish Archives of Pediatrics/Türk Pediatri Arşivi. Published December 25, 2018. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6568286/","responses":[{"text":"Gestational diabetes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic endocrine tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus type 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes of the young","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3464,"text":"Which of the following is a rich source of iodine?","explanation":"**Seafood** is a rich source of iodine.\r\n\r\nIodine is an essential trace element required for the synthesis of thyroid hormones, which play a crucial role in regulating metabolism and overall body function. Seafood, especially fish and seaweed, is known to be a particularly abundant source of iodine. Oceans and seawater contain a significant amount of iodine, and marine organisms concentrate this element in their tissues.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 406.","responses":[{"text":"Seafood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Egg yolk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diary products","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chicken breast","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3493,"text":"A person with cardiovascular disease wants to decrease his low-density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol level. What would be the preferred suggestion?","explanation":"The preferred suggestion for a person with cardiovascular disease who wants to decrease their low-density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol level is **statins**.\r\n\r\nStatins, also known as HMG-CoA reductase inhibitors, are a class of drugs that effectively lower LDL cholesterol levels in the blood. They work by inhibiting the enzyme HMG-CoA reductase, which is involved in cholesterol synthesis. By reducing cholesterol production in the liver, statins lead to increased uptake and clearance of LDL cholesterol from the bloodstream, resulting in decreased LDL levels.\r\n\r\nNiacin and fibrates are also used to modify lipid levels, but they primarily target triglycerides and HDL cholesterol rather than LDL cholesterol. Exercise and weight loss can have some positive effects on cholesterol levels, but they are generally not as potent as statins in lowering LDL cholesterol and are often recommended as complementary lifestyle measures alongside medication.\r\n\r\nFor individuals with cardiovascular disease, statins are the first-line treatment to reduce LDL cholesterol and lower the risk of cardiovascular events.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 290.","responses":[{"text":"Weight loss","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Statins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrates","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3527,"text":"Which of the following symptoms is associated with hypothyroidism?","explanation":"**Drowsiness** is associated with hypothyroidism.\r\n\r\nHypothyroidism is a condition characterized by an underactive thyroid gland, leading to decreased production of thyroid hormones. Thyroid hormones play a crucial role in regulating metabolism and various body functions. When their levels are low, it can result in a range of symptoms.\r\n\r\nDrowsiness or fatigue is a common symptom of hypothyroidism. Patients may feel excessively tired and lack energy despite getting enough sleep. Other common symptoms include weight gain, cold intolerance, constipation, dry skin, and hair loss.","reference":"(1) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 346.\r\n\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1097.","responses":[{"text":"Drowsiness","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperthermia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachypnea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Profuse sweating","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3551,"text":"Which of the following is an action of insulin?","explanation":"**Increase K+ uptake** is an action of insulin.\r\n\r\nInsulin is a hormone produced by the beta cells of the pancreas and plays a critical role in regulating glucose metabolism. Its main function is to facilitate the uptake of glucose into cells, reducing blood glucose levels. However, insulin also has other important actions in the body.\r\n\r\nOne of these actions is the **stimulation of cellular uptake of potassium (K+)**. Insulin enhances the activity of the Na+/K+ ATPase pump on the cell membrane, which leads to increased uptake of potassium into cells. As a result, insulin helps lower the concentration of potassium in the bloodstream, maintaining proper potassium balance and preventing hyperkalemia.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 384.","responses":[{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease blood pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase K+ uptake","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase Na+ uptake","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase Ca+ uptake","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9541,"text":"While operating on the pituitary gland, a surgeon tried to secure the optic chiasma. Which of the following structures separates the pituitary from the optic chiasma?","explanation":"The **diaphragma sellae** is a fold of dura mater that separates the pituitary gland from the optic chiasma within the sella turcica of the sphenoid bone.\r\n\r\nDuring pituitary surgery, the surgeon must be cautious not to damage the optic chiasma, which is a crucial structure for visual function. The diaphragma sellae acts as a protective barrier, forming the roof of the sella turcica and creating a physical separation between the pituitary gland and the optic chiasma.\r\n\r\nThe cavernous sinus is a venous sinus located on either side of the sella turcica, and it contains important structures like the internal carotid artery and cranial nerves. The dorsum sellae is a bony ridge at the posterior edge of the sella turcica. The sphenoidal body is a part of the sphenoid bone, and the sphenoidal sinus is an air-filled cavity within the sphenoid bone.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 883-884.","responses":[{"text":"Diaphragmatic sellae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenoidal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenoidal body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsum sellae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cavernous sinus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9542,"text":"The pituitary gland is a pea-sized gland that plays a major role in regulating vital body functions and general well-being.  It is referred to as the body's master gland because it controls the activity of most other hormone-secreting glands. What part of the anterior pituitary gland is mainly responsible for hormone secretion?","explanation":"The pituitary gland is a small, pea-sized gland located at the base of the brain. It consists of two main parts: the anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis) and the posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis).\r\n\r\nThe **Pars anterior**  is responsible for the secretion of several important hormones, which play a vital role in regulating various body functions and maintaining general well-being. Some of the hormones secreted by the anterior pituitary include:\r\n\r\n1. **Growth hormone (GH)**: Stimulates growth, protein synthesis, and tissue repair.\r\n\r\n2. **Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH)**: Stimulates the adrenal glands to secrete cortisol, which is involved in the stress response and metabolism.\r\n\r\n3. **Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)**: Stimulates the thyroid gland to produce thyroid hormones that regulate metabolism.\r\n\r\n4. **Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH)** and **Luteinizing hormone (LH)**: Regulate the reproductive system and sex hormone production.\r\n\r\n5. **Prolactin (PRL)**: Stimulates milk production in lactating females.\r\n\r\nThe anterior pituitary is under the control of releasing and inhibiting hormones produced in the **hypothalamus**. These hormones travel through the blood vessels connecting the hypothalamus and the anterior pituitary, regulating the secretion of specific hormones.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 929.\r\n(2)Ilahi S, Ilahi TB. Anatomy, adenohypophysis(Pars anterior, anterior pituitary). In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519039/","responses":[{"text":"Pars nervosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars tuberalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars anterior","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars intermedia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9544,"text":"The attachments of sternothyroid and sternohyoid muscles prevents the extension of an enlarged thyroid gland in which direction?","explanation":"The attachments of the sternothyroid and sternohyoid muscles prevent the extension of an enlarged thyroid gland **superiorly.**\r\n\r\nThe sternothyroid muscle originates from the posterior surface of the manubrium of the sternum, while the sternohyoid muscle originates from the posterior surface of the medial end of the clavicle and the superior border of the first rib. Both muscles then insert into the oblique line of the thyroid cartilage.\r\n\r\nWhen the thyroid gland becomes enlarged, a condition known as goiter, it can exert pressure on surrounding structures. The sternothyroid and sternohyoid muscles, being attached to the thyroid cartilage, help limit the superior expansion of an enlarged thyroid gland. This prevents the goiter from extending upward into the neck and compressing vital structures in that region.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1010.","responses":[{"text":"Inferiorly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superiorly","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posteriorly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Laterally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anteriorly","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9545,"text":"A patient has developed hoarseness of voice, a day after surgical resection of the thyroid gland. The complaint has developed due to injury of which of the following?","explanation":"The patient's hoarseness of voice after surgical resection of the thyroid gland is most likely due to injury of the **recurrent laryngeal nerve.**\r\n\r\nThe recurrent laryngeal nerve is a branch of the vagus nerve (cranial nerve X) that innervates the intrinsic muscles of the larynx, which are responsible for vocal cord movements. During thyroid surgery, especially in cases of thyroidectomy, the recurrent laryngeal nerve is at risk of injury due to its anatomical course around the thyroid gland.\r\n\r\nInjury to the recurrent laryngeal nerve can result in paralysis or weakness of the muscles it innervates, leading to hoarseness of voice and even vocal cord paralysis in severe cases. This complication is more common after surgeries involving the thyroid gland, as the nerve courses close to or within the thyroid gland.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1053, 1091.","responses":[{"text":"Internal laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phrenic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recurrent laryngeal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"External laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9546,"text":"A 50-year-old male patient came into the outpatient department with yellowish pigmentation of the skin, itching, and was diagnosed as a case of obstructive jaundice. What is the most likely cause of this patient's jaundice?","explanation":"The most likely cause of obstructive jaundice in this 50-year-old male patient is **cancer in the head of the pancreas.**\r\n\r\nObstructive jaundice occurs when there is a blockage of the bile ducts, leading to impaired bile flow from the liver to the duodenum. The common causes of obstructive jaundice include gallstones, tumors, and strictures.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the patient's symptoms of yellowish skin pigmentation (jaundice) and itching are classic manifestations of obstructive jaundice. The location of the obstruction is important in identifying the cause. Cancer in the head of the pancreas can cause compression and obstruction of the common bile duct, leading to the backflow of bile into the bloodstream, resulting in jaundice.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 893.","responses":[{"text":"Perforated ulcer of the stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cancer in the head of pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforation of duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cancer in the body of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstruction of main pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9547,"text":"An old hypertensive patient is suffering from ischemia of the suprarenal gland. This condition is most likely due to occlusion of direct branches from which of the following arteries?","explanation":"In an old hypertensive patient with ischemia of the suprarenal gland, the most likely cause is occlusion of direct branches from the **aorta, inferior phrenic, and renal arteries.**\r\n\r\nThe **suprarenal glands (adrenal glands)** receive their blood supply from three arteries: the superior suprarenal artery (branch of the inferior phrenic artery), the middle suprarenal artery (branch of the aorta), and the inferior suprarenal artery (branch of the renal artery).\r\n\r\nIschemia of the suprarenal glands can have various clinical manifestations, including adrenal insufficiency and symptoms related to the stress response regulation.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 521.","responses":[{"text":"Superior mesenteric, inferior mesenteric, and aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aorta, superior mesenteric, and renal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aorta, inferior phrenic, and renal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal, hepatic, and aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal, superior mesenteric, and inferior mesenteric","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9548,"text":"Which of the following is not part of the stroma of the thyroid gland?","explanation":"The stroma of the thyroid gland is the supportive connective tissue framework that surrounds and supports the functional units of the gland, known as **thyroid follicles**. However, the thyroid follicles themselves are not part of the stroma.\r\n\r\nThe stroma of the thyroid gland is composed of various components, including **reticular connective tissue, lymphocytes, macrophages, a true capsule formed by a thin layer of connective tissue,** and **septae dividing the gland into lobules.**\r\n\r\n**Thyroid follicles**, on the other hand, are the structural and functional units of the thyroid gland responsible for the synthesis and storage of thyroid hormones. Each thyroid follicle is composed of a central lumen filled with colloid, a protein-rich material containing thyroglobulin, the precursor of thyroid hormones. The follicular cells surrounding the colloid are responsible for synthesizing, storing, and releasing thyroid hormones into the bloodstream.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 156.","responses":[{"text":"Reticular connective tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid follicles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"True capsule formed by thin layer of connective tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes and macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septae dividing the gland into lobules","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9549,"text":"Pheochromocytoma is a medical condition in which the patient experiences tachycardia (increased heart rate), hypertension, excessive sweating, and headaches. It involves which following part of the adrenal gland?","explanation":"Pheochromocytoma is a rare neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the **adrenal medulla**, the inner part of the adrenal gland. The adrenal medulla is responsible for producing and secreting catecholamines, such as adrenaline (epinephrine) and noradrenaline (norepinephrine), which are important hormones involved in the body's \"fight or flight\" response.\r\n\r\nIn pheochromocytoma, the tumor cells in the adrenal medulla produce excessive amounts of catecholamines, leading to a surge in circulating adrenaline and noradrenaline. As a result, the patient experiences various symptoms, including tachycardia (increased heart rate), hypertension (high blood pressure), excessive sweating, and headaches. These symptoms are all characteristic of the effects of elevated catecholamines on the cardiovascular and autonomic nervous systems.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 172.","responses":[{"text":"Zona fasciculate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona pellucida","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal medulla","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona glomerulosa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9550,"text":"In a post-lecture feedback exam under a microscope, students were unable to distinguish stained sections of the pancreas revealing two different types of parenchymal tissue. The histologist hinted that the light-stained clusters of cells are the ones producing hormones that underlie the endocrine functions of the pancreas. What is the lightly stained section?","explanation":"The pancreas is a complex organ with both endocrine and exocrine functions. The **islets of Langerhans**, also known as pancreatic islets, are the lightly stained clusters of cells scattered throughout the **parenchyma** of the pancreas. These islets are responsible for the endocrine functions of the pancreas, as they contain several types of hormone-producing cells.\r\n\r\nWithin the islets, there are mainly four types of hormone-secreting cells:\r\n1. **Alpha cells** secrete glucagon, which increases blood glucose levels.\r\n2. **Beta cells** secrete insulin, which lowers blood glucose levels.\r\n3. **Delta cells** secrete somatostatin, which inhibits the release of insulin and glucagon.\r\n4. **Pancreatic polypeptide cells** secrete pancreatic polypeptide, which regulates various gastrointestinal activities.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 427.","responses":[{"text":"Acini","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stroma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parenchyma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Capsule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Islets of Langerhan","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9551,"text":"On examining histological slides, the students get confused between the alpha cells and beta cells, forgetting their location in the pancreas. They were informed that the location of alpha cells is in which of the following?","explanation":"The pancreas is a glandular organ with both endocrine and exocrine functions. The endocrine portion of the pancreas consists of clusters of hormone-secreting cells known as islets of Langerhans. These islets contain different types of cells, including alpha cells and beta cells.\r\n\r\n**Alpha cells** are responsible for producing the hormone **glucagon**, which plays a key role in increasing blood glucose levels. These cells are predominantly located towards the **periphery of the islets**. On the other hand, **beta cells** are responsible for producing the hormone **insulin**, which helps in lowering blood glucose levels, and they are mainly found in the **center of the islets**.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 427.","responses":[{"text":"Towards the center of islets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Near the periphery of islets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Only in the center of islets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Equally in both regions of islets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only in the periphery of islets","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9552,"text":"Blood mineralocorticoid levels, specifically aldosterone, of a 45-year-old male were found to be on the lower side. The zone of the adrenal gland that is responsible for the synthesis of these hormones is which of the following?","explanation":"Aldosterone is a mineralocorticoid hormone that plays a crucial role in the regulation of electrolyte and water balance in the body, particularly by influencing the reabsorption of sodium and the excretion of potassium in the kidneys. The synthesis and secretion of aldosterone primarily occur in the **zona glomerulosa** of the **adrenal cortex**.\r\n\r\nThe adrenal cortex is the outer part of the adrenal gland and is composed of three distinct zones: the zona glomerulosa, zona fasciculata, and zona reticularis. Each zone is responsible for producing different groups of steroid hormones.\r\n\r\nIn the **zona glomerulosa**, the cells contain the necessary enzymes and receptors to produce mineralocorticoids, with aldosterone being the principal mineralocorticoid hormone. The secretion of aldosterone is primarily regulated by the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS) and is responsive to changes in blood pressure, sodium levels, and potassium levels.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 424.","responses":[{"text":"Zona fasciculata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromaffin cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona glomerulosa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9553,"text":"The two main parts of the adrenal gland have different embryonic origins. The inside of the adrenal medulla is neural crest in origin. The outside of the adrenal cortex is derived from mesenchyme (mesothelium). Which of the following parts of the adrenal gland regresses after birth?","explanation":"The adrenal gland is composed of two distinct parts with different embryonic origins: the **adrenal medulla** and the **adrenal cortex**.\r\n\r\nThe **adrenal medulla** arises from **neural crest cells**, which are a group of cells that originate from the neural tube during embryonic development. These cells migrate to the developing adrenal gland and differentiate into chromaffin cells, which are responsible for producing and releasing catecholamines such as epinephrine (adrenaline) and norepinephrine (noradrenaline). The adrenal medulla is an important component of the sympathetic nervous system and plays a role in the body's response to stress and emergencies.\r\n\r\nThe **adrenal cortex**, on the other hand, is derived from **mesoderm**, specifically the **mesenchyme** or **mesothelium**. It is further divided into three zones: the zona glomerulosa, zona fasciculata, and zona reticularis. The cells in these zones are responsible for producing various steroid hormones, including aldosterone, cortisol, and androgens.\r\n\r\nAmong the components of the adrenal cortex, the **adrenal cortex inner zone** (sometimes referred to as the zona intermedia) is a transient structure that undergoes regression after birth. This zone is more prominent during fetal development and is less prominent in the adult adrenal gland.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 346.","responses":[{"text":"Zona fasciculata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal cortex inner zone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona glomerulosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9554,"text":"Somatotrophs are cells of the anterior pituitary gland which secrete which of the following?","explanation":"Somatotrophs are specialized cells in the anterior pituitary gland responsible for secreting **growth hormone (GH)**, also known as somatotropin. GH plays a crucial role in regulating growth, metabolism, and body composition. Its primary target tissues include bones, cartilage, and muscles.\r\n\r\nUpon stimulation by the hypothalamic hormone **growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH)**, somatotrophs release GH into the bloodstream. Conversely, the release of GH is inhibited by **somatostatin (SST)**, which is another hormone produced by the hypothalamus.\r\n\r\nGH promotes growth and development in children and adolescents by stimulating the production of insulin-like growth factors (IGFs) in the liver and other tissues. In adults, GH continues to regulate metabolism and body composition, influencing fat metabolism and protein synthesis.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 417.","responses":[{"text":"Adrenocorticotrophic hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid stimulating hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle stimulating hormone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9555,"text":"The growth hormone binds to its cell surface receptor and activates which of the following?","explanation":"When the growth hormone (GH) binds to its cell surface receptor, it activates the **tyrosine kinase activity** of the receptor. The GH receptor is a member of the cytokine receptor superfamily, which lacks intrinsic enzymatic activity. However, upon GH binding, the receptor undergoes dimerization, leading to the activation of associated Janus Kinases (JAKs). The JAKs then phosphorylate specific tyrosine residues on the intracellular domain of the receptor.\r\n\r\nThe phosphorylated tyrosine residues serve as docking sites for various signaling molecules, including STAT proteins. Once recruited to the receptor, STAT proteins are also phosphorylated by JAKs, leading to their dimerization and translocation to the nucleus. In the nucleus, STAT proteins regulate the transcription of specific target genes, ultimately mediating the cellular responses to GH, such as growth, metabolism, and cell proliferation.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 343.","responses":[{"text":"cGMP production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium and diacylglycerol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cAMP production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine kinase activity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inositol triphosphate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9556,"text":"In the absence of ADH, the permeability of the distal tubules and collecting ducts to water is low, causing the kidneys to excrete large amounts of dilute urine. This condition is known as which of the following?","explanation":"The condition described, where the kidneys excrete large amounts of dilute urine due to low water permeability in the distal tubules and collecting ducts in the absence of antidiuretic hormone (ADH), is known as **Diabetes Insipidus (DI)**.\r\n\r\nDI is a disorder characterized by a deficiency or reduced response to ADH, also known as vasopressin. ADH plays a crucial role in regulating water reabsorption in the kidney tubules, particularly in the distal tubules and collecting ducts. When ADH is lacking or not functioning properly, these renal tubules fail to reabsorb water effectively, leading to the excretion of large volumes of diluted urine.\r\n\r\nThere are two main types of diabetes insipidus: **central diabetes insipidus** and **nephrogenic diabetes insipidus**. Central DI results from insufficient production or release of ADH by the hypothalamus or pituitary gland. Nephrogenic DI, on the other hand, occurs when the kidneys are unresponsive to the action of ADH.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 432.","responses":[{"text":"Central diabetes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrogenic diabetes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes insipidus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gestational diabetes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9557,"text":"Which of the following is the transporter responsible for the transport of iodine into the thyroid cells against the concentration gradient?","explanation":"**Na+/I- symport** is a specific transport mechanism that actively transports **iodine (I-)** into the thyroid cells from the bloodstream, **against the concentration gradient**. This process is coupled with the movement of **sodium ions (Na+)** into the cell, utilizing the electrochemical gradient of sodium. The concentration of iodine inside the thyroid cell is higher than in the surrounding bloodstream, enabling the synthesis of thyroid hormones.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 941.","responses":[{"text":"K+, I- symport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+, I- symport","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+, glucose symport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"I-/Cl- antiport","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9558,"text":"Vitamin D acts on intestinal epithelial cells and forms which proteins to facilitate calcium absorption?","explanation":"Vitamin D plays a crucial role in maintaining calcium homeostasis in the body. When vitamin D is activated, it acts on the **intestinal epithelial cells** to increase the production of a calcium-binding protein called **Calbindin**.\r\n\r\n**Calbindin** is a cytoplasmic protein that binds to calcium ions in the intestinal cells, allowing for efficient transport of calcium across the intestinal epithelium. It enhances the absorption of calcium from the gut lumen into the bloodstream, thereby increasing calcium levels in the body.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 999.","responses":[{"text":"Calsequestrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calbindin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcineurin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9559,"text":"In the process of release of insulin, beta cells of the pancreas get depolarized by which of the following?","explanation":"When blood glucose levels rise, the beta cells of the pancreas respond by releasing insulin to regulate glucose uptake and utilization in the body. The process of insulin release involves a series of events, and depolarization of the beta cells is a critical step.\r\n\r\nWhen glucose enters the beta cells, it undergoes glycolysis and produces ATP. The increased intracellular ATP levels lead to the **ATP-dependent closure of K+ channels**, which prevents the efflux of K+ from the cell. This causes the cell to become depolarized.\r\n\r\nDepolarization opens **voltage-gated Ca2+ channels**, and Ca2+ enters the cell. The increased intracellular Ca2+ triggers the exocytosis of insulin-containing vesicles, leading to the release of insulin into the bloodstream.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 979.","responses":[{"text":"ATP-dependant closure of Ca2+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP-dependant closure of K+ channels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Entry of Ca2+ by voltage gated channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entry of Na+ by voltage gated channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP-dependant opening of K+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9579,"text":"A woman underwent thyroidectomy (removal of the thyroid). After a few days, she comes in with paresthesia and spasm. After investigation, a diagnosis was made for hypocalcemia due to hypoparathyroidism due to incidental parathyroid gland removal. Where does the incidentally removed gland develop from?","explanation":"The incidentally removed parathyroid gland develops from the **3rd and 4th pharyngeal pouches** during embryonic development.\r\n\r\nThe parathyroid glands are small, endocrine glands located in the neck region, usually on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland. They are responsible for the production and secretion of parathyroid hormone (PTH), which plays a vital role in calcium and phosphate homeostasis in the body.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, the parathyroid glands originate from the pharyngeal pouches, which are specialized structures derived from the primitive pharynx. The 3rd and 4th pharyngeal pouches give rise to the **parathyroid glands** and the **thymus**, respectively. As these structures develop, they migrate to their final positions in the neck region. The parathyroid glands usually remain closely associated with the thyroid gland, while the thymus migrates lower into the anterior mediastinum.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"3rd and 4th pharyngeal pouch","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rathke's pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharyngeal cleft","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachial arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachial plate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9580,"text":"Which of the following hormones does not act through cAMP?","explanation":"**Oxytocin** is the hormone that does not act through cAMP. \r\n\r\nHormones can exert their effects on target cells through various mechanisms, and one common signaling pathway is the cAMP (cyclic adenosine monophosphate) pathway. **Epinephrine, FSH, LH, and Glucagon** all act through the cAMP pathway.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, **Oxytocin** is a peptide hormone that acts through a different intracellular signaling mechanism. It primarily acts through the activation of phospholipase C (PLC), leading to the formation of inositol trisphosphate (IP3) and diacylglycerol (DAG). These second messengers then trigger a calcium-dependent signaling pathway, resulting in smooth muscle contraction in the uterus during childbirth and milk ejection from the mammary glands during lactation.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 924.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 343.","responses":[{"text":"Oxytocin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone (LH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9581,"text":"Polyuria can occur in which of the following?","explanation":"**Polyuria** is the condition characterized by the production of abnormally large volumes of urine. Among the options provided, **Diabetes Mellitus** is the correct answer for the cause of polyuria.\r\n\r\n**Diabetes Mellitus:** In diabetes mellitus, either due to insufficient insulin production (Type 1 diabetes) or inadequate response to insulin (Type 2 diabetes), blood glucose levels remain elevated. The elevated glucose in the bloodstream exceeds the renal threshold, causing glucose to spill into the urine (glucosuria). The presence of glucose in the urine leads to an osmotic effect, pulling water with it and increasing the urine volume. Consequently, patients with diabetes may experience increased frequency of urination and produce large amounts of urine, a classic symptom of polyuria.\r\n\r\nWhile other conditions mentioned in the options can also lead to increased urine production, diabetes mellitus is the most common and significant cause of polyuria in the given list.","reference":"Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology 13th ed, pg 427","responses":[{"text":"Diarrhoea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infections","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9582,"text":"Low energy levels in the body stimulate the secretion of which of the following?","explanation":"**Glucagon** is secreted in response to low energy levels in the body.\r\n\r\nGlucagon is a peptide hormone produced by the alpha cells of the pancreas. It acts in opposition to insulin, which is produced by the beta cells of the pancreas. When blood glucose levels drop, such as during fasting or exercise, the body requires an alternative source of energy to maintain normal physiological functions.\r\n\r\nIn this situation, glucagon is released into the bloodstream. Its primary target is the liver, where it stimulates the breakdown of glycogen into glucose (glycogenolysis) and the formation of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors (gluconeogenesis). By increasing blood glucose levels, glucagon helps to provide a constant supply of energy to the body's tissues, especially the brain and muscles.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 982.","responses":[{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9583,"text":"What is the number of amino acids in the polypeptide glucagon?","explanation":"The polypeptide **glucagon** consists of **29 amino acids** in its sequence.\r\n\r\nGlucagon is a peptide hormone produced by the alpha cells of the pancreas. It plays a crucial role in regulating blood glucose levels by stimulating glycogenolysis (breakdown of glycogen to glucose) and gluconeogenesis (formation of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors) in the liver. This leads to an increase in blood glucose levels, especially during periods of fasting or low blood glucose.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 982.","responses":[{"text":"39","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"31","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"29","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"21","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"51","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9584,"text":"Glucagon is a peptide hormone. The primary target for glucagon is the liver, where its action is mediated by which of the following second messenger systems?","explanation":"Glucagon is a peptide hormone produced and secreted by the alpha cells of the pancreas. Its primary role is to regulate blood glucose levels. When blood glucose levels are low, glucagon is released to stimulate glucose production and release from the liver into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\n**Glucagon binds to specific receptors on the surface of hepatocytes (liver cells), which activates the enzyme adenylate cyclase. Adenylate cyclase converts ATP to cAMP**, a secondary messenger molecule. cAMP, in turn, activates protein kinase A (PKA), which leads to a series of intracellular events.\r\n\r\nOne of the major effects of PKA activation is the stimulation of glycogenolysis (breakdown of glycogen to release glucose) and gluconeogenesis (production of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors) in the liver. This raises blood glucose levels, restoring them to normal.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 924.","responses":[{"text":"Nuclear receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cAMP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"cIMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DNA receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9585,"text":"Hormone secretions from the posterior pituitary include which of the following?","explanation":"The posterior pituitary gland does not synthesize hormones itself; rather, it stores and releases two hormones that are produced by the hypothalamus. These hormones are oxytocin and vasopressin (ADH).\r\n\r\n**1. Oxytocin:** Oxytocin is a peptide hormone that plays a vital role in various reproductive functions. It stimulates uterine contractions during labor and delivery and promotes milk ejection during breastfeeding. Additionally, oxytocin is involved in social bonding and maternal behaviors.\r\n\r\n**2. Vasopressin (ADH):** Vasopressin is an antidiuretic hormone that regulates water balance in the body. It acts on the kidneys, promoting water reabsorption, and reducing urine output. This helps maintain body fluid balance and prevents dehydration.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 917.","responses":[{"text":"Leptin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxytocin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroxin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9586,"text":"What is the amino acid used as a pre-requisite in the biosynthesis of catecholamines and thyronine?","explanation":"**Tyrosine** is the amino acid used as a pre-requisite in the biosynthesis of catecholamines (such as dopamine, norepinephrine, and epinephrine) and thyroid hormones (thyronine).\r\n\r\nIn the first step of catecholamine biosynthesis, tyrosine is hydroxylated by the enzyme **tyrosine hydroxylase** to form **L-dihydroxyphenylalanine (L-DOPA)**. L-DOPA is further decarboxylated to form dopamine, which serves as a precursor for norepinephrine and epinephrine.\r\n\r\nIn the biosynthesis of thyroid hormones, tyrosine residues in the protein thyroglobulin are iodinated. The iodinated tyrosine residues are then coupled together to form thyronine, which is a precursor for the synthesis of the thyroid hormones **triiodothyronine (T3)** and **thyroxine (T4)**.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 285.","responses":[{"text":"Glutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylalanine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9587,"text":"Which hormone secreted from the anterior pituitary stimulates progesterone release?","explanation":"**Luteinizing hormone (LH)**, secreted from the anterior pituitary, stimulates progesterone release from the ovaries.\r\n\r\nDuring the menstrual cycle, the surge in LH levels triggers ovulation. Following ovulation, the ruptured follicle transforms into the corpus luteum under the influence of LH. The corpus luteum is a temporary endocrine structure that produces progesterone.\r\n\r\nProgesterone plays a crucial role in preparing the endometrium for implantation of a fertilized egg and maintaining early pregnancy if conception occurs. It also helps regulate the menstrual cycle and prevents further ovulation during pregnancy.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 918.","responses":[{"text":"Progestins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chorionic gonadotropin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenocorticotropin hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicular stimulating hormone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9589,"text":"A 55-year-old man complains of muscle weakness and dizziness for 4 months. His blood pressure is 190/105 mmHg. Laboratory results show hypernatremia, hypokalemia, elevated serum aldosterone, and low renin and angiotensin. Blood urea nitrogen (BUN) is 26 mg/dL, and creatinine is 1.3 mg/dL. The attending physician rules out Cushing syndrome. Which of the following is the most likley cause of hypertension in this patient?","explanation":"The most likely cause of hypertension in this patient is **Conn syndrome**, also known as primary hyperaldosteronism.\r\n\r\nConn syndrome is characterized by the excessive production of aldosterone by the adrenal glands, leading to increased sodium retention and potassium loss in the kidneys. This results in hypertension, hypokalemia (low potassium levels), and hypernatremia (elevated sodium levels).\r\n\r\nThe patient's clinical presentation of muscle weakness, dizziness, and elevated blood pressure, along with laboratory findings of hypernatremia, hypokalemia, and elevated serum aldosterone, are consistent with the diagnosis of Conn syndrome.\r\n\r\nIt is important to rule out other possible causes, such as Cushing syndrome, which can also present with hypertension and muscle weakness but is associated with elevated cortisol levels rather than aldosterone.\r\n\r\nConfirmation of the diagnosis can be done through the measurement of plasma aldosterone to renin ratio, which is elevated in Conn syndrome.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1119-1120.","responses":[{"text":"Pheochromocytoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conn syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenogenital syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic adrenal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9590,"text":"A 16-year-old is brought to the emergency department with diabetic ketoacidosis. Upon checking blood glucose levels, he is diagnosed with type 1 diabetes. Insulin is administered and advised for the future as well. What is the cause of his condition?","explanation":"DKA is a severe complication of type 1 diabetes mellitus and can occur when there is an absolute deficiency of insulin in the body. In type 1 diabetes, the pancreas fails to produce insulin, leading to uncontrolled hyperglycemia. In the absence of sufficient insulin, glucose cannot enter cells to provide energy, leading to increased lipolysis (breakdown of fat) and proteolysis (breakdown of proteins) to meet the body's energy demands.\r\n\r\nThe increased lipolysis results in the release of free fatty acids, which are converted into ketone bodies in the liver. The excess ketone bodies, such as acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate, accumulate in the blood, causing the characteristic metabolic acidosis seen in DKA.\r\n\r\nInsulin administration is essential in the management of DKA as it helps reverse the metabolic abnormalities by promoting glucose uptake by cells, inhibiting lipolysis, and reducing ketogenesis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1106.","responses":[{"text":"Reduced gluconeogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced proteolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced lipolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased ketogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased ketogenesis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9591,"text":"A 61-year-old diabetic comes into the emergency room. His laboratory results shows a random blood sugar of 890 mg/dL and serum osmolarity of 460 mOsm. The patient is dehydrated and confused. What is this condition known as?","explanation":"**Hyperosmolar Hyperglycemic Nonketotic Syndrome** is a severe complication of uncontrolled diabetes mellitus. It typically occurs in older adults with type 2 diabetes. The patient's presentation of a random blood sugar level of 890 mg/dL and serum osmolarity of 460 mOsm indicates severe hyperglycemia and dehydration.\r\n\r\nHHNS is characterized by extreme hyperglycemia without significant ketosis, unlike diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), which presents with both hyperglycemia and ketosis. The absence of ketosis in HHNS is due to adequate insulin levels that prevent the breakdown of fat into ketones.\r\n\r\nPatients with HHNS often present with dehydration, confusion, altered consciousness, and other neurological symptoms. It is crucial to correct the hyperglycemia and provide intravenous fluids to rehydrate the patient.","reference":"Adeyinka A, Kondamudi NP. Hyperosmolar hyperglycemic nonketotic coma. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 24, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482142/","responses":[{"text":"Renal tubular acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic ketoacidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperosmolar hyperglycemic nonketotic syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9592,"text":"A 55-year-old housewife presents to the clinic with complaints of feeling tired and partaking in heavy daytime sleepiness. She also complains of breathlessness and feeling cold all the time. Her face is puffy with dry, coarse skin. She has a dull expression on her face and her tongue protrudes from her mouth. Further examination shows midline neck swelling and edema of her legs. Which laboratory investigation will be the most useful in diagnosing her condition?","explanation":"Based on the clinical presentation described, the patient is exhibiting signs and symptoms suggestive of hypothyroidism. The key features such as tiredness, heavy daytime sleepiness, cold intolerance, puffy face, dry skin, and dull expression are typical of hypothyroidism. The presence of midline neck swelling and edema of the legs further raises suspicion for a thyroid disorder.\r\n\r\nMeasurement of **serum thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) levels** is the initial and most sensitive test for assessing thyroid function. In primary hypothyroidism, which is the most common cause of hypothyroidism, TSH levels will be elevated as the pituitary gland attempts to stimulate the thyroid gland to produce more thyroid hormones. Subsequently, the thyroid gland fails to respond adequately, leading to decreased levels of thyroid hormones, particularly **T4 (thyroxine)**.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 346.","responses":[{"text":"Serum TSH levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound scan of her neck swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radio iodine uptake scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9593,"text":"Hypothyroidism is caused by structural or functional derangement that interferes with thyroid hormone production. Which of the following statements regarding hypothyroidism is correct?","explanation":"The correct statement regarding hypothyroidism is that **Hashimoto thyroiditis** is an important cause in the developed world. Hashimoto thyroiditis, also known as chronic lymphocytic thyroiditis, is an autoimmune disorder where the body's immune system attacks the thyroid gland, leading to inflammation and gradual destruction of thyroid tissue. This results in decreased thyroid hormone production and eventually hypothyroidism.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1078.","responses":[{"text":"In infants, it results in myxoedema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Most common cause in iodine deficient areas of Pakistan is Grave's diesease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hashimoto thyroiditis is an important cause in the developed world","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid opthalmopathy with proptosis is a common feature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Throughout the world, hypothyroidism is associated with zinc deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9597,"text":"Physical examination of a neonate shows a markedly virilized and hypertrophic clitoris with partial fusion of the labioscrotal folds in a female having 46, XX karyotype. Laboratory studies will most likely reveal a deficiency of which of the following?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of a markedly virilized and hypertrophic clitoris with partial fusion of the labioscrotal folds in a female neonate suggests a condition known as **congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH)**. CAH is a group of autosomal recessive disorders caused by enzyme deficiencies in the adrenal steroid biosynthesis pathway, leading to impaired synthesis of various hormones.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the most likely deficiency is of the enzyme **21-hydroxylase**, which is responsible for the conversion of 17-hydroxyprogesterone to 11-deoxycortisol in the adrenal gland. The lack of 21-hydroxylase results in impaired synthesis of cortisol and aldosterone and leads to an accumulation of precursors, including **androstenedione**.\r\n\r\nThe excess androstenedione, a weak androgen, causes the virilization of external genitalia in females. Additionally, the deficiency of cortisol stimulates an increase in adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) secretion, leading to adrenal hyperplasia and excess production of adrenal androgens.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1121.","responses":[{"text":"Corticotropin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"21-hydroxylase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Androstenedione","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9604,"text":"Autopsy of an 8-week-old infant reveals massive bilateral adrenal enlargement, who died after developing severe dehydration and hypotension. Hypovolemic shock in this infant was most likely caused by inadequate synthesis of which of the following hormones?","explanation":"The infant's presentation with massive bilateral adrenal enlargement and death due to severe dehydration and hypotension suggests a condition known as **congenital adrenal hyperplasia** (CAH). CAH is a group of autosomal recessive disorders caused by enzyme deficiencies in the adrenal steroid biosynthesis pathway, leading to impaired synthesis of various hormones.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the inadequate synthesis of **aldosterone**, a mineralocorticoid hormone, is responsible for the hypovolemic shock. Aldosterone plays a crucial role in regulating sodium and potassium levels in the body and maintaining blood volume and blood pressure by promoting sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion in the kidneys.\r\n\r\nThe deficiency of aldosterone in CAH results in decreased sodium reabsorption, leading to excessive loss of sodium and water in the urine, ultimately causing dehydration and hypotension. Additionally, the lack of aldosterone can lead to hyperkalemia, contributing to further electrolyte imbalances and cardiovascular instability.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1124.","responses":[{"text":"Renin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antidiuretic hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial natriuretic factor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9605,"text":"A plump child presents with multiple issues to a clinic and the mother complains that he eats a lot. The physician explains that these types of children are at high risk of becoming overweight adolescents and adults, putting them at risk of developing chronic diseases such as heart disease and diabetes later in life. This condition occurs due to abnormal growth of adipose tissue because of enlargement of the fat cell or increase in fat cell number. The condition is known as which of the following?","explanation":"The child's presentation, being plump and eating excessively, raises concerns about the development of **obesity**. Obesity is a condition characterized by excessive accumulation of adipose tissue due to either enlargement or an increase in the number of fat cells. It results from an energy imbalance, where caloric intake exceeds energy expenditure, leading to the storage of excess fat.\r\n\r\nUnlike **kwashiorkor** and **marasmus**, which are forms of severe malnutrition, obesity is caused by excessive nutrient intake, especially high-calorie and high-fat foods. Inactivity, sedentary lifestyle, and lack of physical activity are significant contributors to the development of obesity. However, obesity itself is not a consequence of inactivity but rather the result of a combination of dietary habits and low energy expenditure.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1104.","responses":[{"text":"Sedentary style","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Kwashiorkor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marasmus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inactivity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9606,"text":"Which one of these is not a causative factor of diabetes mellitus?","explanation":"Diabetes mellitus is a metabolic disorder characterized by elevated blood glucose levels due to impaired insulin action or secretion. Several factors contribute to the development of diabetes mellitus, and the correct answer is **increased physical activity**.\r\n\r\n**Genetics** plays a significant role in diabetes susceptibility. Family history of diabetes increases the risk of developing the condition, highlighting the importance of genetic predisposition.\r\n\r\n**Increased central obesity** and being **overweight** are both risk factors for type 2 diabetes. Excess adipose tissue in the abdominal region contributes to insulin resistance, leading to impaired glucose regulation.\r\n\r\n**Ethnicity** is also a significant factor. Certain ethnic groups, such as African Americans, Hispanic Americans, and Asian Americans, have a higher predisposition to diabetes compared to others.\r\n\r\nHowever, **increased physical activity** has a beneficial effect in diabetes prevention. Regular exercise improves insulin sensitivity, aids in weight management, and reduces the risk of developing diabetes.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1102-1104.","responses":[{"text":"Increased physical activity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethnicity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genetics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased central obesity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overweight","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9607,"text":"The best indicator for monitoring the impact of iodine deficiency disorder control program is which of the following?","explanation":"The best indicator for monitoring the impact of an iodine deficiency disorder control program is **\"urinary iodine levels.\"**\r\n\r\nUrinary iodine levels reflect the amount of iodine that individuals are consuming through their diet. Iodine is an essential nutrient required for the synthesis of thyroid hormones, which play a crucial role in maintaining normal growth, development, and metabolism. In areas with iodine deficiency, individuals may not get enough iodine in their diet, leading to various health problems, including goiter and hypothyroidism.\r\n\r\nBy measuring urinary iodine levels in a population, public health authorities can assess the adequacy of iodine intake and the effectiveness of interventions to control iodine deficiency disorders. A significant decrease in urinary iodine levels following the implementation of an iodine supplementation program or iodized salt distribution indicates improved iodine intake and reduced risk of iodine deficiency-related health issues. Monitoring urinary iodine levels is, therefore, a valuable tool for evaluating the success of iodine deficiency control programs.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Neonatal hypothyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevalence of goitre among school children","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodine level in soil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinary iodine levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodine level in water","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9608,"text":"Traits are defined as which of the following?","explanation":"Traits are defined as \"relatively enduring characteristics that influence our behavior across many situations.\"\r\n\r\nPersonality traits are stable and consistent patterns of thoughts, emotions, and behaviors that individuals exhibit over time. These traits play a crucial role in shaping how individuals perceive the world, interact with others, and respond to various situations. Traits are considered relatively enduring because they tend to be consistent and predictable across different contexts and over time.\r\n\r\nThe Five-Factor Model (also known as the Big Five personality traits) is a widely accepted framework for understanding personality, and it includes five main dimensions: Openness to Experience, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, and Neuroticism. Each of these dimensions represents a broad spectrum of traits that individuals may possess to varying degrees.","reference":"(1) Stangor C, Walinga J. 12. 1 personality and behaviour: approaches and measurement. Published online October 17, 2014. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://opentextbc.ca/introductiontopsychology/chapter/11-1-personality-and-behavior-approaches-and-measurement/\r\n\r\n(2) McCabe KO, Fleeson W. Are traits useful? Explaining trait manifestations as tools in the pursuit of goals. Journal of personality and social psychology. Published February 2016. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4718867/","responses":[{"text":"Brain regions that differ in different people","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Permanent personality characteristics that distinguish us from other people","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Relatively enduring characteristics that influence our behavior across many situations","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Unconscious tendencies to act in different ways according to the situation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physical characteristics that distinguish us from other people","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9609,"text":"A girl is friendly, always willing to help others, and compassionate. We should expect her to score highly on which of the following?","explanation":"Personality traits are often assessed using the Five-Factor Model, which includes five broad dimensions: openness to experience, conscientiousness, extraversion, agreeableness, and neuroticism (OCEAN). \r\n\r\n**Extraversion** is a personality trait characterized by sociability, assertiveness, and a preference for being around others. Individuals high in extraversion are often friendly, outgoing, and enjoy social interactions. They tend to be more energized by social situations and seek out opportunities to engage with others.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, \"Agreeableness\" is a personality trait related to kindness, empathy, and cooperativeness, which can also be evident in the girl's description. It is important to note that people can possess multiple personality traits to varying degrees, and personality is a complex and multifaceted construct.","reference":"(1) Five-factor model of personality. obo. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.oxfordbibliographies.com/view/document/obo-9780199828340/obo-9780199828340-0120.xml\r\n\r\n(2) Extraversion - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/psychology/extraversion","responses":[{"text":"Introversion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oppenness to experience","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neuroticism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Agreeableness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extraversion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9610,"text":"A 30-year-old man presents to the medical outpatient department with complaints of headache for the past 2 days. Pain is moderate in intensity and associated with blurring of vision. On examination, he has a blood pressure of 160/90 mmHg and body mass index (BMI) of 30 kg/m^2. Which of the following is required to fulfill the definition of metabolic syndrome?","explanation":"**The diagnosis of metabolic syndrome requires the presence of at least three of the following five criteria:**\r\n\r\n1. **Impaired fasting glucose:** This means fasting blood sugar levels are higher than normal but not high enough to be diagnosed as diabetes.\r\n\r\n2. **Increased triglyceride levels:** High levels of triglycerides in the blood.\r\n\r\n3. **Decreased HDL cholesterol:** Low levels of \"good\" HDL cholesterol.\r\n\r\n4. **Raised blood pressure:** Hypertension, with systolic blood pressure of 130 mmHg or higher, or diastolic blood pressure of 85 mmHg or higher.\r\n\r\n5. **Central obesity (increased BMI):** Defined as a body mass index (BMI) of 30 kg/m² or higher.\r\n\r\nIn the given scenario, the patient has an elevated BMI (30 kg/m²) along with hypertension (blood pressure of 160/90 mmHg), which meets two criteria for metabolic syndrome. However, the information provided is not sufficient to determine if the patient meets the other criteria.\r\n\r\n**The following additional information is required to fulfill the definition of metabolic syndrome:**\r\n\r\n- Fasting blood glucose levels\r\n- Triglyceride levels\r\n- HDL cholesterol levels","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1103.","responses":[{"text":"Impaired fasting glucose, increased triglycerides, decreased HDL, raised uric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"History of using corticosteroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired fasting glucose, increased triglycerides, decreased HDL","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of acanthosis nigricans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised cholesterol and LDL","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9611,"text":"A 25-year-old man presents to the medical and patient department with complaints of raised blood pressure for the past 2 months. He has no significant past medical history. On examination, he is looking obese. Which of the following criterion is used for the diagnosis of insulin resistance syndrome?","explanation":"According to the American Association of Clinical Endocrinologists (AACE) guidelines, the diagnosis of metabolic syndrome is made when a patient has three or more of the following five criteria:\r\n\r\n1. **Central Obesity**: Measured by waist circumference. The cutoff values vary based on ethnicity but generally are ≥40 inches (102 cm) for men and ≥35 inches (88 cm) for women.\r\n\r\n2. **Elevated Triglycerides**: Fasting triglyceride level ≥150 mg/dL (1.7 mmol/L).\r\n\r\n3. **Reduced HDL Cholesterol**: Fasting HDL cholesterol level \u003c40 mg/dL (1.0 mmol/L) in men or \u003c50 mg/dL (1.3 mmol/L) in women.\r\n\r\n4. **Elevated Blood Pressure**: Blood pressure ≥130/85 mmHg or current use of antihypertensive medication.\r\n\r\n5. **Elevated Fasting Glucose**: Fasting blood glucose level ≥100 mg/dL (5.6 mmol/L).\r\n\r\nThe presence of these three or more criteria indicates the presence of metabolic syndrome. The syndrome is associated with insulin resistance, a state in which the body's cells do not respond properly to insulin, leading to high blood glucose levels.","reference":"Goff DC, Lloyd-Jones DM, Bennett G, et al. 2013 acc/aha guideline on the assessment of cardiovascular risk: a report of the american college of cardiology/american heart association task force on practice guidelines. Circulation. Published June 24, 2014. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/01.cir.0000437741.48606.98","responses":[{"text":"Presence of acanthosis nigericans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fasting blood glucose value of 80-100mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HDL \u003e 50mg/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Triglyceride greater than 150mg/dL","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood pressure reading 120/80mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9612,"text":"A 40-year-old woman presents to a medical specialist with a complaint of excessive hair growth over the face. She is diagnosed with a case of metabolic syndrome. Which of the following should be included during the evaluation of patients for metabolic syndrome?","explanation":"**All of these** should be included during the evaluation of patients for metabolic syndrome.\r\n\r\nMetabolic syndrome is a cluster of risk factors that increase the risk of cardiovascular diseases, type 2 diabetes, and other health complications. To diagnose metabolic syndrome, healthcare providers evaluate a combination of key measurements and risk factors.\r\n\r\n1. **BMI (Body Mass Index) calculation:** BMI is used to assess whether a person's weight is within a healthy range for their height. It helps identify obesity, a major component of metabolic syndrome.\r\n\r\n2. **Lipid profile:** This includes measuring levels of total cholesterol, LDL cholesterol, HDL cholesterol, and triglycerides. Dyslipidemia (abnormal lipid levels) is another component of metabolic syndrome.\r\n\r\n3. **Measurement of fasting blood sugar:** Elevated fasting blood sugar levels are associated with insulin resistance, a hallmark of metabolic syndrome.\r\n\r\n4. **Measurement of vital signs:** Vital signs such as blood pressure are essential to identify hypertension, another component of metabolic syndrome.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1103.","responses":[{"text":"All of these","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"BMI calculation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measurement of vital signs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measurement of fasting blood sugar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipid profile","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9613,"text":"A 30-year-old man presents to the outpatient department for a workup of obesity. He is diagnosed with a case of metabolic syndrome. The first step in the prevention of metabolic syndrome is which of the following?","explanation":"The first step in the prevention of metabolic syndrome is **effective lifestyle interventions**, focusing on nutrition and exercise.\r\n\r\nMetabolic syndrome is a cluster of risk factors that increase the likelihood of developing cardiovascular diseases, type 2 diabetes, and other health complications. It is characterized by obesity, elevated blood pressure, high blood sugar levels, high triglycerides, and low HDL cholesterol.\r\n\r\nWhile medical treatments and pharmacotherapy may be necessary in some cases, the initial and most essential approach is to address lifestyle factors. **Caloric restriction** and **regular exercise** play a central role in reducing weight, improving insulin sensitivity, and decreasing the risk of cardiovascular events.\r\n\r\nNutrition should focus on a balanced and healthy diet, with an emphasis on whole grains, fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, and healthy fats while reducing the intake of processed foods, sugars, and unhealthy fats.\r\n\r\nEngaging in regular physical activity helps burn calories, improve insulin sensitivity, and enhance overall cardiovascular health.","reference":"Grundy SM, Cleeman JI, Daniels SR, et al. Diagnosis and management of the metabolic syndrome. Circulation. Published October 25, 2005. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/circulationaha.105.169404","responses":[{"text":"Liposuction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin administration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Effective lifestyle interventions, focusing on nutrition and exercise","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Caloric restriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharmacotherapy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9620,"text":"Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) is most effective in stimulating the secretion of which of the following?","explanation":"**ACTH** is most effective in stimulating the secretion of **hydrocortisone (cortisol)** from the adrenal cortex.\r\n\r\nACTH is a hormone produced and released by the anterior pituitary gland in response to the releasing hormone **corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH)** from the hypothalamus. ACTH primarily acts on the adrenal cortex to stimulate the synthesis and release of glucocorticoids, including hydrocortisone (cortisol). The production of cortisol is essential for various physiological processes, such as regulating carbohydrate, protein, and lipid metabolism, as well as suppressing the immune system's inflammatory responses. ACTH specifically targets the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex, where cortisol is synthesized and secreted in response to ACTH stimulation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 851-852.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal androgen hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrocortisone (cortisol)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10322,"text":"A 54-year-old, married woman para-2 comes to the clinic with the complaint of weight gain and lethargy for the past 3 months. She had her last menstrual period 6 years back. Her blood pressure is 150/90 mmHg, her pulse is 65/min, and is regular bilaterally. Her body mass index (BMI) falls in the obese range. Her eyes are puffy, she complains of breathlessness, and cold intolerance, her skin is coarse and her abdomen has white striations present. What is the best diagnostic test for this woman?","explanation":"The best diagnostic test for this 54-year-old woman is **serum TSH level**. Her clinical presentation is highly suggestive of hypothyroidism. The symptoms of weight gain, lethargy, cold intolerance, puffy eyes, and coarse skin are typical features of hypothyroidism. Additionally, her blood pressure is elevated, which can be seen in hypothyroidism.\r\n\r\nIn this case, measuring the serum TSH level is crucial because an elevated TSH level along with low levels of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4) would confirm the diagnosis of primary hypothyroidism. Primary hypothyroidism is the most common cause of hypothyroidism and is characterized by inadequate thyroid hormone production due to dysfunction of the thyroid gland itself.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1086.","responses":[{"text":"Serum cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral glucose tolerance test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral glucose tolerance test and TSH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum TSH level","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum cortisol and TSH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10954,"text":"Steroid hormones work by which of the following mechanisms?","explanation":"Steroid hormones exert their effects primarily by **stimulating mRNA transcription**.\r\n\r\nSteroid hormones are lipophilic molecules that can easily cross cell membranes and enter target cells. Once inside the cell, they bind to specific intracellular receptors, forming hormone-receptor complexes. These complexes then translocate to the cell nucleus, where they interact with specific DNA sequences called **hormone response elements (HREs)** in the regulatory regions of target genes. This binding activates the transcription of messenger RNA (mRNA) from the target genes. The newly synthesized mRNA is then translated into specific proteins, leading to the biological effects of the steroid hormones. This process allows steroid hormones to regulate gene expression and protein synthesis, influencing various cellular functions and physiological processes.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 923.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibition of protein synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modification of enzymes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stimulation of mRNA transcription","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stimulation of DNA replication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Second messenger","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10955,"text":"A student observes a slide of tissue from an organ that has cells arranged in two distinct inner and outer layers. It is a slide of the suprarenal gland. What structure is the outer layer derived from?","explanation":"The outer layer of the suprarenal (adrenal) gland is derived from **mesenchyme**.\r\n\r\nThe suprarenal gland consists of two distinct regions: the outer cortex and the inner medulla. The **cortex**, which forms the outer layer, arises from **mesenchyme**. During development, mesenchymal cells migrate to the area where the suprarenal gland will form, and they subsequently differentiate into various cell types of the cortical region. The **medulla**, on the other hand, derives from **neural crest cells**, a unique population of cells that migrate along the neural tube during embryonic development. These neural crest cells give rise to the chromaffin cells of the medulla, which produce catecholamines (epinephrine and norepinephrine).","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 259.","responses":[{"text":"Mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesenchyme","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neural crest cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoderm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10956,"text":"A 26-year-old patient comes to the outpatient department with a painless swelling in the neck for 2 months, anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. What is the probable diagnosis?","explanation":"A cervical cyst refers to a **fluid-filled sac or pouch** that develops in the neck region. It often presents as a painless, palpable swelling, most commonly found anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. Cervical cysts can arise from various origins, including congenital developmental anomalies or retention of fluid within ducts or tissues. Thyroglossal cyst and thyroglossal duct are specific types of cervical cysts that occur due to the **incomplete closure of the thyroglossal duct**, a structure that connects the thyroid gland to the developing tongue during fetal development. However, in this case, the general term \"cervical cyst\" is used, indicating a non-specific fluid-filled swelling in the neck.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 164.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroglossal duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervical cyst","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroglossal cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory thyroid gland","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10957,"text":"A 22-year-old patient comes to the outpatient department with a painless swelling in the midline of the neck, inferior to the hyoid bone. What is the probable diagnosis?","explanation":"A thyroglossal cyst is a **fluid-filled cystic swelling** that arises from the **persistent remnant** of the **thyroglossal duct**, a structure present during embryonic development that connects the thyroid gland to the developing tongue. As the embryo grows, the thyroid gland migrates from its initial location at the base of the tongue to its final position in the anterior neck. The thyroglossal duct typically degenerates and disappears, but in some cases, remnants may persist, giving rise to thyroglossal cysts. These cysts usually present as midline neck swellings, inferior to the hyoid bone, and they move up with tongue protrusion. They are typically painless but may become infected, leading to tenderness and redness.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 169.","responses":[{"text":"Thyroglossal cyst","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervical cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroglossal duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory thyroid gland","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11131,"text":"Which of the following hormones does not use cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) as a second messenger?","explanation":"**Estrogen** is the hormone that does not use **cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP)** as a second messenger.\r\n\r\nHormones that use cAMP as a second messenger belong to the class of **peptide hormones or protein hormones**. When these hormones bind to their specific receptors on the cell surface, it activates the receptor, leading to the generation of cAMP inside the cell. cAMP then acts as a second messenger, activating protein kinases and initiating various intracellular signaling cascades.\r\n\r\nHowever, **estrogen** is a **steroid hormone**, and it uses a different mechanism for signal transduction. Steroid hormones like estrogen are lipophilic and can cross the cell membrane to bind to intracellular receptors located in the cytoplasm or nucleus. This hormone-receptor complex then directly interacts with specific DNA sequences, regulating gene expression and protein synthesis within the target cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 924.","responses":[{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone (LH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11132,"text":"Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) causes the release of androgens from which of the following regions of the adrenal gland?","explanation":"**ACTH** causes the release of androgens from the **zona reticularis** of the adrenal gland.\r\n\r\nACTH is a hormone produced and secreted by the anterior pituitary gland in response to the releasing hormone **corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH)** from the hypothalamus. ACTH primarily targets the **adrenal cortex**, which is divided into three distinct regions: zona glomerulosa, zona fasciculata, and zona reticularis. Each region synthesizes and secretes different hormones.\r\n\r\nIn response to ACTH stimulation, the **zona reticularis** of the adrenal cortex releases **androgens**, which are precursors to sex hormones. Androgens play essential roles in male and female physiology, influencing sexual development and other physiological processes. The other zones (zona glomerulosa and zona fasciculata) primarily secrete mineralocorticoids (e.g., aldosterone) and glucocorticoids (e.g., cortisol), respectively.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 425.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona fasciculata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona glomerulosa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11133,"text":"Parathyroid hormone (PTH) stimulates the conversion of vitamin D to which of the following forms?","explanation":"**Parathyroid hormone (PTH)** stimulates the conversion of vitamin D to its active form, **calcitriol**.\r\n\r\nParathyroid hormone (PTH) is a hormone produced by the parathyroid glands in response to low blood calcium levels. One of its essential roles is to regulate calcium and phosphate levels in the body. PTH indirectly influences the activation of vitamin D, which is a vital process for maintaining calcium homeostasis.\r\n\r\nWhen blood calcium levels decrease, PTH is released, and it acts on the kidneys to stimulate the conversion of inactive vitamin D (calcidiol) to its active form, **calcitriol**. Calcitriol is the most potent form of vitamin D and plays a crucial role in increasing intestinal calcium and phosphate absorption, promoting bone resorption, and maintaining calcium balance.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Ergocalciferol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecalciferol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitriol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcidiol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11134,"text":"Organification is a term used for the binding of which of the following?","explanation":"**Organification** is a term used to describe the process of **binding iodine to thyroglobulin** within the thyroid gland during thyroid hormone synthesis.\r\n\r\nThyroid hormone synthesis involves the incorporation of iodine into the amino acid tyrosine, which is a part of a large glycoprotein called **thyroglobulin**, found in the colloid of thyroid follicles. The first step in this process is the active transport of **iodide (I⁻)** from the bloodstream into thyroid follicular cells. Once inside the cells, iodide is oxidized to reactive iodine (I₂) by an enzyme called **thyroid peroxidase (TPO)**. This iodine then binds to specific tyrosine residues on the thyroglobulin molecule, forming **monoiodotyrosine (MIT)** or **diiodotyrosine (DIT)**.\r\n\r\nSubsequent coupling of MIT and DIT results in the formation of **thyroxine (T4)** or **triiodothyronine (T3)**, the two biologically active thyroid hormones.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 943.","responses":[{"text":"Iodide to HCO₃-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodide to another iodide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodide to chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodine to thyroglobulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine to thyroglobulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11135,"text":"Which of the following layers of the adrenal cortex has a vacuolated or spongy appearance in routine histological preparations due to washing of the lipids droplets?","explanation":"The **zona fasciculata** is the layer of the adrenal cortex that has a **vacuolated or spongy appearance** in routine histological preparations due to the washing away of lipid droplets.\r\n\r\nThe adrenal cortex is composed of three distinct layers: zona glomerulosa, zona fasciculata, and zona reticularis. Each zone is responsible for the synthesis and secretion of specific hormones.\r\n\r\nIn the **zona fasciculata**, cells produce and secrete **glucocorticoids**, primarily **cortisol**. These cells are rich in **lipid droplets** containing the precursor for cortisol synthesis. During routine histological processing, the lipids are washed away during tissue preparation, resulting in a **vacuolated or spongy appearance** in the zona fasciculata when observed under a microscope.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 424.","responses":[{"text":"Zona fasciculata","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona glomerulosa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11136,"text":"Which of the following is the main method of the \"control of iodine deficiency program in Pakistan\" to reduce iodine deficiency?","explanation":"The main method of the \"control of iodine deficiency program in Pakistan\" to reduce iodine deficiency is to **promote iodized salt consumption**.\r\n\r\nIodine deficiency can lead to various health issues, including **goiter** and **mental retardation**. To combat iodine deficiency disorders (IDD), many countries, including Pakistan, have implemented iodine supplementation programs. The most common and cost-effective method is the iodization of table salt.\r\n\r\nIodized salt contains a controlled amount of iodine, ensuring that people receive an adequate daily intake of this essential micronutrient. Regular consumption of iodized salt helps prevent iodine deficiency, especially in regions where iodine-rich foods are scarce or not easily accessible.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Endocrinology module, Community medicine slides, Topic: Iodine Control Program.","responses":[{"text":"Promote iodized water consumption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Promote iodized salt consumption","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Promote the consumption of iodized oil in capsule or injection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Promote the consumption of iodine rich foods","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11137,"text":"When does the thyroid gland come in front of the trachea during development?","explanation":"The thyroid gland comes in front of the trachea during development in the **7th week** of gestation. At this stage, the thyroid gland starts to develop from an endodermal thickening in the floor of the primitive pharynx known as the thyroid diverticulum. It then descends anteriorly and migrates down the neck until it reaches its final position in front of the trachea.\r\n\r\nDuring the **3rd week**, the thyroid diverticulum begins to form, and by the **5th month**, the gland becomes functional, secreting thyroid hormones that play a crucial role in fetal development and growth. However, it's the **7th week** when the thyroid gland becomes visible as a small bud in front of the trachea.\r\n\r\nAfter birth, the thyroid gland continues to grow and develop, and it remains located in the front of the trachea throughout life.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 169.","responses":[{"text":"3rd week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7th week","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"5th month","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"During fetal period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At birth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11138,"text":"Allah Rakha, a 30-year-old, takes insulin in overdose, due to which he develops\r\nhypoglycemia. Which of the following will occur to bring his glucose level back to normal?","explanation":"**Increased growth hormone, increased glucagon, increased epinephrine** will occur to bring Allah Rakha's glucose level back to normal.\r\n\r\nWhen a person takes an insulin overdose, it leads to an excess uptake of glucose by cells, causing hypoglycemia (low blood glucose levels). In response to hypoglycemia, the body activates counter-regulatory mechanisms to increase blood glucose levels and prevent potential harm to the brain and other vital organs.\r\n\r\n**Glucagon**, a hormone produced by the alpha cells of the pancreas, is released in response to low blood glucose. Glucagon stimulates the liver to release stored glycogen as glucose into the bloodstream, raising blood glucose levels.\r\n\r\n**Epinephrine** (adrenaline), which is released from the adrenal glands, also plays a crucial role in counteracting hypoglycemia. Epinephrine increases glucose production by promoting glycogen breakdown in the liver (glycogenolysis) and stimulates glucose release into the blood.\r\n\r\n**Growth hormone (GH)** levels increase during hypoglycemia, and GH has both insulin-like and anti-insulin effects, contributing to the increase in blood glucose levels.","reference":"1) Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 943-944, 992.\r\n2) Hoffman RP. Sympathetic mechanisms of hypoglycemic counterregulation. Current Diabetes Reviews. Published August 2007. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18220670/","responses":[{"text":"Decreased growth hormone, increased glucagon, increased epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased growth hormone, decreased glucagon, decreased epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased growth hormone, increased glucagon, decreased epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased growth hormone, increased glucagon, increased epinephrine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased growth hormone, increased glucagon, epinephrine constant","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11139,"text":"Which of the following hormones binds to intra-nuclear receptors?","explanation":"**Thyroid hormone** binds to intra-nuclear receptors.\r\n\r\nIntra-nuclear receptors are located inside the cell nucleus and directly interact with DNA to regulate gene expression. Thyroid hormones, including thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3), are unique among the listed hormones as they bind to intra-nuclear receptors.\r\n\r\nOnce thyroid hormones enter the target cells, they are converted to their active form, T3, by intracellular enzymes. T3 then binds to specific thyroid hormone receptors (TR) within the cell nucleus. This hormone-receptor complex interacts with specific DNA sequences known as thyroid hormone response elements (TREs) on target genes. This interaction leads to the activation or repression of gene transcription, ultimately affecting various cellular processes, including metabolism, growth, and development.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 944.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid hormone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11140,"text":"A 35-year-old female comes to the clinic with symptoms of hypothyroidism. The physician is concerned about thyroid auto-antibodies. Which antibody is most commonly observed in Hashimoto thyroiditis?","explanation":"**Anti-peroxidase antibodies** (also known as anti-thyroid peroxidase or anti-TPO antibodies) are most commonly observed in Hashimoto thyroiditis.\r\n\r\nHashimoto thyroiditis is an autoimmune disease in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks the thyroid gland, leading to chronic inflammation and gradual destruction of thyroid tissue. The presence of anti-peroxidase antibodies is a hallmark of this condition.\r\n\r\nThyroid peroxidase is an enzyme that plays a crucial role in the production of thyroid hormones. In Hashimoto thyroiditis, the immune system produces antibodies against this enzyme, leading to impaired thyroid hormone synthesis and secretion. As a result, the thyroid gland becomes enlarged (goiter) and fails to produce sufficient thyroid hormones, leading to hypothyroidism.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 163.","responses":[{"text":"Anti-follicular antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-cytoplasmic antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-peroxidase antibodies","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-nuclear antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11155,"text":"Which hormone is involved in the ejection of milk from mammary glands during lactation?","explanation":"During lactation, the hormone responsible for the ejection of milk from the mammary glands is **oxytocin**. Oxytocin is produced in the hypothalamus and released from the posterior pituitary gland in response to stimulation of the nipples during breastfeeding.\r\n\r\nWhen a baby suckles at the breast, nerve signals are transmitted to the hypothalamus, which then triggers the release of oxytocin. Oxytocin acts on the myoepithelial cells surrounding the milk-producing mammary gland alveoli. It causes these cells to contract, leading to the ejection of milk into the ducts and eventually out of the nipple, making it available for the baby to feed.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, **prolactin** is another hormone involved in lactation. It is also produced in the pituitary gland and stimulates the production of milk in the mammary glands. Prolactin is responsible for initiating and maintaining milk production, while oxytocin is responsible for milk ejection.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 940.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxytocin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatomammotropin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11156,"text":"Which of the following stimulates the release of growth hormone?","explanation":"The release of growth hormone (GH) from the anterior pituitary gland is mainly regulated by the **hypothalamus** through the secretion of **growth hormone-releasing hormone (GHRH)** and **somatostatin**. These hypothalamic hormones modulate the secretion of GH in response to various physiological factors.\r\n\r\n**Deep sleep** is a significant stimulator of GH release. During deep sleep, the secretion of GHRH is increased, leading to a subsequent increase in GH release. This is one of the reasons why children, who spend more time in deep sleep, have higher levels of GH, contributing to their growth and development.\r\n\r\n**Somatomedins**, also known as insulin-like growth factors (IGFs), are hormones produced by the liver and other tissues in response to GH stimulation. They mediate many of the growth-promoting effects of GH, but they are not responsible for stimulating GH release itself.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 933.","responses":[{"text":"Deep sleep","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased body free fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aging","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased blood glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatomedins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11157,"text":"A 30-year-old patient presents with anorexia after suffering from a head trauma one week ago. Which hypothalamic nucleus is involved in the regulation of thirst and hunger?","explanation":"The **lateral nucleus** of the hypothalamus is involved in the regulation of both thirst and hunger.\r\n\r\n1. **Thirst Regulation:** The lateral hypothalamic area contains neurons that are responsible for triggering thirst sensations. When the body's water levels are low or when there is an increase in the concentration of solutes in the blood, these neurons are activated, leading to the sensation of thirst. Thirst is an essential mechanism that helps maintain proper water balance in the body.\r\n\r\n2. **Hunger Regulation:** The lateral hypothalamic area also plays a significant role in the regulation of hunger. Neurons in this region are involved in stimulating appetite and food intake. When these neurons are activated, it leads to feelings of hunger and an increased desire to eat.","reference":"Castro DC, Cole SL, Berridge KC. Lateral hypothalamus, nucleus accumbens, and ventral pallidum roles in eating and hunger: interactions between homeostatic and reward circuitry. Frontiers in Systems Neuroscience. Published June 15, 2015. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4466441/","responses":[{"text":"Anterior nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral nucleus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11159,"text":"During the examination of the adrenal gland, the immunohistochemical staining shows three zones of the adrenal gland in an adult, but only two zones are visible in the fetus and zona reticularis is absent. What is the reason for its absence?","explanation":"The correct reason for the absence of zona reticularis in the fetus is that **zona reticularis is not fully developed during the fetal period**.\r\n\r\nThe adrenal gland is a dynamic organ that undergoes significant changes during fetal development. Initially, in the fetus, the adrenal gland consists of two primary zones: the **zona glomerulosa** and the **zona fasciculata**. These two zones are responsible for producing mineralocorticoids and glucocorticoids, respectively.\r\n\r\nAs the fetal period progresses, around the third trimester, the third zone called **zona reticularis** starts to develop between the zona glomerulosa and zona fasciculata. Zona reticularis is responsible for producing androgens, which are sex hormones.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 346.","responses":[{"text":"There are only two zones in adrenal gland and zona reticularis does not exist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis is not present during the fetal period","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a congenital defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis is present only in 1 percent population","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Specific staining techniques are required to observe zona reticularis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11161,"text":"Which of the following lowers the plasma level of ionized calcium?","explanation":"**Calcitonin** is the hormone that lowers the plasma level of **ionized calcium**.\r\n\r\nCalcitonin is a hormone secreted by the **parafollicular (C) cells** of the thyroid gland. It plays a crucial role in calcium homeostasis by counteracting the actions of parathyroid hormone (PTH). When blood calcium levels are elevated, calcitonin is released, and it acts on bones to **inhibit osteoclast activity**, which reduces bone resorption and decreases the release of calcium into the blood. This results in a decrease in the plasma level of ionized calcium. Although calcitonin is involved in calcium regulation, its contribution to overall calcium balance is relatively minor compared to PTH, which has a more significant role in increasing blood calcium levels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1002.","responses":[{"text":"Parathyroid hormone related protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcitonin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathyroid hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11162,"text":"Iodine transport in follicular cells of the thyroid gland is an example of which type of transport?","explanation":"Iodine transport in the follicular cells of the thyroid gland is an example of **secondary active transport**. This process involves the movement of iodine against its concentration gradient, from the bloodstream into the thyroid follicular cells. Secondary active transport utilizes the energy stored in the sodium gradient, which is established by primary active transport (specifically, the sodium-potassium ATPase pump). The sodium gradient provides the driving force for the symport of iodine and sodium through a specific transporter located on the basolateral membrane of the follicular cells.\r\n\r\nAs sodium ions move down their concentration gradient into the cell, they bring iodine along with them against its concentration gradient. Once inside the follicular cells, iodine is utilized in the synthesis of thyroid hormones—triiodothyronine (T3) and thyroxine (T4). These hormones play crucial roles in regulating metabolism, growth, and development throughout the body.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 942.","responses":[{"text":"Simple diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary active transport","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11164,"text":"A child presents with very tall height and large viscera and is diagnosed with gigantism. Increased activity of which cells of the anterior pituitary are responsible for this condition?","explanation":"The increased activity of **somatotrophs** in the anterior pituitary is responsible for the condition of **gigantism** in the child.\r\n\r\nGigantism is a rare condition that occurs due to excessive secretion of growth hormone (GH) during childhood and adolescence when the epiphyseal growth plates are still open. This unrestrained production of GH is caused by hyperactivity of the **somatotrophs**—the cells in the anterior pituitary that synthesize and release GH. As a result, the child experiences accelerated linear growth, leading to a very tall stature and enlargement of visceral organs.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1071.","responses":[{"text":"Mammotrophs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyrotrophs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticotrophs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonadotrophs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatotrophs","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11170,"text":"A pathologist was observing a tissue specimen from a parathyroid gland. He noticed small glandular cells that constitute 80% of the gland mass and secrete parathyroid hormone. What type of cell is this most likely to be?","explanation":"The small glandular cells that constitute 80% of the gland mass and secrete **parathyroid hormone (PTH)** are most likely **chief/ principal cells**.\r\n\r\nThe primary functional cells in the parathyroid glands are the **chief/ principal cells**, which synthesize and secrete PTH. These cells are small, polyhedral, and densely packed with secretory granules containing PTH. PTH acts on bones, kidneys, and intestines to increase blood calcium levels by stimulating bone resorption, promoting calcium reabsorption in the kidneys, and increasing intestinal calcium absorption.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 432.","responses":[{"text":"Interstitial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxyphil cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicular cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chief/ principal cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11171,"text":"Which of the following are seen with lactotroph adenoma?","explanation":"**Galactorrhea**, **amenorrhea**, and **infertility** are characteristic features associated with **lactotroph adenoma**.\r\n\r\nLactotroph adenoma is a type of **pituitary adenoma** that arises from lactotroph cells, which secrete **prolactin**, a hormone responsible for lactation and reproductive functions. When a lactotroph adenoma develops, it can lead to **excessive prolactin secretion** (hyperprolactinemia). Elevated prolactin levels interfere with the normal menstrual cycle, resulting in **amenorrhea** (absence of menstruation) and decreased fertility, leading to **infertility**. Additionally, elevated prolactin levels can stimulate milk production in the breast, causing **galactorrhea** (abnormal lactation) even in non-pregnant or non-lactating individuals. Increased libido (sexual desire) is not typically associated with lactotroph adenoma.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1071.","responses":[{"text":"Galactorrhea, amenorrhea, increased libido","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Galactorrhea, polymenorrhea, increased libido","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Galactorrhea, amenorrhea, infertility","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Galactorrhea, increased libido, infertility","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11172,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism or thyrotoxicosis?","explanation":"**Graves disease** is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism or thyrotoxicosis.\r\n\r\nHyperthyroidism refers to the condition of excessive thyroid hormone production and secretion. **Graves disease**, an autoimmune disorder, is the most prevalent cause of hyperthyroidism. In Graves disease, the body produces autoantibodies called **thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins (TSI)** that act like thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). These TSI antibodies bind to and activate the TSH receptors on thyroid follicular cells, leading to unregulated production and release of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4). This results in an overactive thyroid gland, causing symptoms such as increased heart rate, weight loss, heat intolerance, and nervousness.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1076.","responses":[{"text":"Hashimoto thyroiditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Graves disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous thyroiditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subacute lymphocytic thyroiditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11173,"text":"A person is diagnosed with hypothyroidism and goiter. Her laboratory tests most likely show which of the following?","explanation":"Hypothyroidism is a condition characterized by an underactive thyroid gland, leading to low levels of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4) in the blood. It often presents with an enlarged thyroid gland, known as a goiter.\r\n\r\nIn primary hypothyroidism, the problem lies within the thyroid gland itself, resulting in decreased production of T3 and T4. When the thyroid hormone levels in the blood are low, the hypothalamus releases thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH), which stimulates the anterior pituitary gland to secrete thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). TSH, in turn, stimulates the thyroid gland to produce more T3 and T4.\r\n\r\nTherefore, in hypothyroidism with goiter, the laboratory tests are likely to show:\r\n\r\n1. **Increased TSH:** The anterior pituitary gland produces more TSH to try and stimulate the thyroid gland to produce more thyroid hormones.\r\n\r\n2. **Decreased T3 and T4:** Due to the underactive thyroid gland, the levels of T3 and T4 are reduced.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1078.","responses":[{"text":"Increased TSH and decreased T3, T4","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased TSH and increased T3, T4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased TSH and increased T3, T4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased TSH and decreased T3, T4","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11174,"text":"Cortisol increases protein concentration in which of the following?","explanation":"Cortisol increases protein concentration in **plasma**.\r\n\r\n Cortisol is a steroid hormone produced by the adrenal cortex. It is essential for various metabolic processes, including protein metabolism. Cortisol stimulates protein catabolism in peripheral tissues such as muscle and skin, but it also increases **protein synthesis** in the liver. This leads to an overall increase in protein concentration in the plasma, as newly synthesized proteins are released into the bloodstream. Cortisol plays a vital role in providing amino acids for gluconeogenesis during stress and maintaining adequate blood glucose levels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 852.","responses":[{"text":"Bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11175,"text":"Which of the following is a feature of oxyphil cells?","explanation":"A feature of **oxyphil cells** is that they are **larger than principal cells**.\r\n\r\n Oxyphil cells have a **larger size** compared to the main functional cells of the parathyroid glands, known as **principal cells**. These cells are **eosinophilic** (acidophilic) due to their high content of mitochondria, which is why they stain pink with eosin. Although the exact function of oxyphil cells is not entirely understood, they are believed to be derived from principal cells and might play a role in calcium metabolism or adaptation to changes in physiological conditions.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Their number decreases with age","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are larger than principal cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They have a basophilic cytoplasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They give rise to principal cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11180,"text":"Which of the following is not related to the histology of parathyroid glands?","explanation":"One of the features of **oxyphil cells** is that they are **larger than principal cells**.\r\n\r\nOxyphil cells are larger and less numerous than the main functional cells of the parathyroid glands, known as **principal cells**. Oxyphil cells have an **eosinophilic** (acidophilic) cytoplasm, making them easily distinguishable from principal cells, which have a **basophilic** (basophilic) cytoplasm. While the function of oxyphil cells is not entirely clear, they are believed to be derived from principal cells and might have a role in calcium metabolism or in cellular adaptation to changes in physiological conditions.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 158.","responses":[{"text":"Stroma has fenestrated capillaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytoplasm is eosinophilic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Separated from the thyroid by a thin capsule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxyphil cells play an important role in regulation plasma calcium levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stroma has reticular and collagen fibers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11181,"text":"A young woman comes into the emergency room experiencing vertigo, nausea, \r\nbradycardia, failure to lactate, and loss of genital and axillary hair. She has given birth one month before and stayed in the hospital for 1 week postpartum. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"The most probable diagnosis for the young woman presenting with vertigo, nausea, bradycardia, failure to lactate, and loss of genital and axillary hair, one month after giving birth and staying in the hospital for one week postpartum, is **Sheehan syndrome**.\r\n\r\nSheehan syndrome, also known as postpartum hypopituitarism, occurs due to severe postpartum hemorrhage and hypotension during childbirth. The excessive blood loss leads to inadequate blood supply to the pituitary gland, resulting in ischemic necrosis (tissue death). As a consequence, there is a deficiency of various pituitary hormones, including **prolactin** (responsible for lactation), **adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH)** (which stimulates cortisol production), and **gonadotropins** (leading to loss of genital and axillary hair due to decreased sex hormone production). Additionally, the symptoms of vertigo and nausea can be attributed to the dysfunction of the anterior pituitary.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 159-160.","responses":[{"text":"MEN syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sheehan syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Graves disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cushing syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Addison disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11199,"text":"In thyrotoxicosis, laboratory tests will most likely show which of the following?","explanation":"In thyrotoxicosis, laboratory tests are most likely to show **increased levels of T3 and T4** (thyroid hormones) and **decreased levels of TSH and TRH**.\r\n\r\nThyrotoxicosis, also known as **hyperthyroidism**, is a condition characterized by excessive production and secretion of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4) from the thyroid gland. The most common cause of hyperthyroidism is Graves' disease, an autoimmune disorder that results in the production of thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins (TSI). These antibodies stimulate the TSH receptor, leading to increased thyroid hormone synthesis and secretion. The elevated levels of T3 and T4 exert negative feedback on the pituitary, leading to a **suppressed TSH secretion**. As a result, TSH and TRH levels are reduced due to the feedback inhibition, resulting in the described laboratory findings.","reference":"Shahid MA, Ashraf MA, Sharma S. Physiology, thyroid hormone. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 25, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500006/","responses":[{"text":"Increased T3, T4, TSH (thyroid-stimulating hormone), and TRH (thyroid-releasing hormone)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased TSH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased T3, T4, and decreased TSH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased T3 and T4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased T3, T4, and decreased TSH, TRH","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11200,"text":"A person comes to the clinic with polydipsia and polyuria with blood glucose levels of 84 mg/dL. Deficiency of which hormone is responsible for this condition?","explanation":"The person's condition of **polydipsia** (excessive thirst) and **polyuria** (increased urination) with normal blood glucose levels (84 mg/dL) is likely due to a deficiency of **antidiuretic hormone**. A deficiency in ADH, or a resistance to its effects, is known as **diabetes insipidus**, which leads to the symptoms of polydipsia and polyuria. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n\r\nAngiotensin II is part of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system and helps regulate blood pressure and fluid balance. \r\n\r\nInsulin is a hormone that helps to lower blood glucose levels by facilitating the uptake of glucose into the cells. While diabetes mellitus, which is associated with insufficient insulin action, can cause polyuria and polydipsia, the blood glucose level in this scenario is normal.\r\n\r\nGlucagon is a hormone that raises blood glucose levels by promoting the release of glucose from liver storage. \r\n\r\nAldosterone helps regulate sodium and potassium levels, as well as blood pressure, by increasing the reabsorption of sodium and water in the kidneys. Aldosterone abnormalities typically present with changes in blood pressure and electrolyte imbalances, not isolated polyuria and polydipsia with normal blood glucose.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 160.","responses":[{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antidiuretic hormone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11201,"text":"A person has diabetes mellitus type-2. The dysfunction of which of the following cells is responsible for this condition?","explanation":"In **diabetes mellitus type 2**, the dysfunction of **beta cells** is responsible for this condition.\r\n\r\nDiabetes mellitus type 2 is characterized by insulin resistance and impaired insulin secretion. **Beta cells** are the specialized cells within the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas that produce and secrete insulin. In type 2 diabetes, there is reduced sensitivity of target tissues to insulin (insulin resistance), leading to a decreased response to insulin's actions. Additionally, over time, beta cells can also undergo **progressive dysfunction and exhaustion** due to chronic hyperglycemia and increased demand for insulin. As a result, insulin secretion becomes inadequate to maintain normal blood glucose levels, contributing to the development of type 2 diabetes.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1099.","responses":[{"text":"Delta cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic polypeptide cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11202,"text":"A 30-year-old woman comes into the clinic with a history of irritability, loose stools, and weight loss. The doctor suspects an autoimmune condition and suggests antibody tests. Antibodies against which of the following will be found?","explanation":"The presence of **TSH-R (thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor) antibodies** will be found in the blood of the 30-year-old woman with a history of irritability, loose stools, and weight loss, suggesting an autoimmune thyroid condition.\r\n\r\nThe symptoms of irritability, loose stools, and weight loss are consistent with **hyperthyroidism**, a condition where there is excessive production of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4). In autoimmune thyroid diseases like **Graves' disease**, the immune system produces antibodies against the TSH-R. These **TSH-R antibodies** bind to the TSH-R on thyroid follicular cells, mimicking the action of TSH and leading to unregulated production of thyroid hormones. This results in an overactive thyroid, hyperthyroidism, and the associated symptoms.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"T4-R","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TSH-R","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TRH-R","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T3-R","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11203,"text":"Epinephrine and nor-epinephrine are derived from which amino acid?","explanation":"**Epinephrine** and **norepinephrine** are derived from the amino acid **tyrosine**.\r\n\r\nBoth hormones are catecholamines produced by the adrenal medulla and certain neurons. The synthesis of epinephrine and norepinephrine starts with the amino acid tyrosine. Tyrosine is first transported into the chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla and neurons. There, it undergoes several enzymatic conversions to form the respective catecholamines. **Epinephrine** is a potent hormone and neurotransmitter responsible for the \"fight or flight\" response, while **norepinephrine** acts as both a hormone and neurotransmitter, regulating various physiological processes.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 285.","responses":[{"text":"Tryptophan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Valine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alanine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11204,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of endogenous Cushing syndrome?","explanation":"The most common cause of **endogenous Cushing syndrome** is **Cushing disease**.\r\n\r\nEndogenous Cushing syndrome results from excessive production of cortisol by the adrenal glands. **Cushing disease** is a specific form of endogenous Cushing syndrome caused by a **pituitary adenoma** (benign tumor) in the pituitary gland. This adenoma leads to increased secretion of **adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH)**, which stimulates the adrenal glands to produce more cortisol. Elevated cortisol levels can cause a wide range of symptoms and complications, affecting various body systems.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 785, 786.","responses":[{"text":"Adrenal adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small cell carcinoma of lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cushing disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11205,"text":"Which of the following is the most potent stimulator of aldosterone secretion?","explanation":"**Hyperkalemia** is the most potent stimulator of **aldosterone** secretion.\r\n\r\n Aldosterone is a hormone produced by the **zona glomerulosa** of the adrenal cortex. Its primary function is to regulate electrolyte balance, particularly **sodium and potassium**, in the body. When **hyperkalemia** occurs (an elevated level of potassium in the blood), the adrenal cortex is stimulated to secrete aldosterone. Aldosterone acts on the distal tubules and collecting ducts of the kidneys, promoting sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion, thus helping to lower blood potassium levels back to normal.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 961.","responses":[{"text":"Hypernatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperkalemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11206,"text":"How does glucagon increase blood glucose levels?","explanation":"**Glucagon** increases blood glucose levels primarily by **increasing glycogenolysis**.\r\n\r\nGlucagon is a hormone produced by the alpha cells of the pancreas in response to low blood glucose levels. When blood glucose levels drop, glucagon is released to promote **glycogenolysis** in the liver. Glycogenolysis involves the breakdown of glycogen, a stored form of glucose, into individual glucose molecules. These glucose molecules are then released into the bloodstream, effectively increasing blood glucose levels. The increased availability of glucose in the bloodstream ensures a continuous supply of energy to meet the body's metabolic demands during fasting or low glucose conditions.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 982.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By increasing glycogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By increasing glycolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By decreasing gluconeogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By increasing glycogenolysis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11207,"text":"Glucocorticoids maintain the blood glucose levels mainly by which of the following processes?","explanation":"**Glucocorticoids** maintain blood glucose levels primarily by **increasing gluconeogenesis**.\r\n\r\nGlucocorticoids act on various tissues, including the liver, to promote the synthesis of new glucose molecules from non-carbohydrate sources. This process, known as **gluconeogenesis**, is crucial for maintaining blood glucose levels during fasting or periods of stress. Glucocorticoids stimulate the conversion of substrates like amino acids and glycerol into glucose precursors in the liver. Subsequently, these precursors are used in gluconeogenesis to synthesize glucose, which is then released into the bloodstream to meet the energy demands of the body.\r\n\r\n**Reference:**\r\n*Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology*, [Latest Edition]. Hall JE. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"By increasing glycogenolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By increasing gluconeogenesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"By increasing glycolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By increasing glycogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11208,"text":"A histology slide showed a section of tissue containing chromaffin cells with abundant fairly\r\nelectron-dense and moderately electron-dense granules. The tissue corresponds to what section of the adrenal gland?","explanation":"The histology slide showing chromaffin cells with abundant fairly electron-dense and moderately electron-dense granules corresponds to the **medulla** of the adrenal gland.\r\n\r\nThe adrenal gland has two main components: the outer cortex and the inner medulla. The cortex is further divided into three zones, namely zona glomerulosa, zona fasciculata, and zona reticularis. Each zone of the cortex produces different steroid hormones, such as aldosterone, cortisol, and sex hormones.\r\n\r\nThe medulla, on the other hand, is responsible for producing catecholamines, including adrenaline (epinephrine) and noradrenaline (norepinephrine). These hormones are stored in chromaffin cells, which contain abundant granules that appear fairly electron-dense and moderately electron-dense on histological slides.\r\n\r\nThe presence of chromaffin cells with these characteristic granules in the tissue section confirms that it corresponds to the medulla of the adrenal gland.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 425.","responses":[{"text":"Medulla","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona glomerulosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona reticularis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zona fasciculata","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11209,"text":"The autoimmune destruction of beta cells results in which of the following diseases?","explanation":"**Diabetes mellitus type 1** is the disease that occurs due to the **autoimmune destruction of beta cells**.\r\n\r\n In **type 1 diabetes mellitus**, the immune system mistakenly identifies the beta cells in the pancreas as foreign and attacks and destroys them. This autoimmune response leads to an **absolute deficiency** of insulin, the hormone responsible for regulating glucose uptake and metabolism. Without sufficient insulin, glucose cannot enter cells, resulting in hyperglycemia and an inability to use glucose as an energy source. Patients with type 1 diabetes require **exogenous insulin** to manage their blood glucose levels.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cushing disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus type-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus type-1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes-insipidus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11210,"text":"Which of the following causes the release of insulin?","explanation":"**Insulin** is released in response to an **increase in blood glucose levels**.\r\n\r\n When blood glucose levels rise after a meal, specialized cells in the pancreas known as **beta cells** detect this increase through their glucose-sensing mechanisms. The rise in blood glucose leads to the influx of glucose into the beta cells, and subsequently, an increase in intracellular ATP levels. Elevated ATP levels result in the closure of ATP-sensitive potassium channels, leading to the **depolarization of beta cells**. This depolarization activates voltage-gated calcium channels, causing an influx of calcium ions. The increased intracellular calcium concentration then triggers the **exocytosis of insulin-containing vesicles**, releasing insulin into the bloodstream.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 979.","responses":[{"text":"Increased glycogenolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased gluconeogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased ketogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in plasma protein concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in blood glucose levels","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11211,"text":"Ketoacidosis occurs in diabetes mellitus type-I due to which of the following?","explanation":"Ketoacidosis in **Type 1 diabetes mellitus** occurs due to **increased gluconeogenesis**.\r\n\r\n In this condition, there is an absolute deficiency of insulin due to autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells. As a result, insulin is insufficient to facilitate glucose entry into cells, leading to a state of cellular starvation. The body responds by increasing **gluconeogenesis** (the synthesis of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors like amino acids and glycerol) to provide an alternative source of energy. However, in the absence of insulin, glucose cannot be effectively utilized, and the body shifts to **lipolysis** (breakdown of fat) for energy production. The excess breakdown of fats results in the accumulation of ketone bodies (acetoacetate and β-hydroxybutyrate), leading to ketoacidosis.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Increased glycogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased gluconeogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased glycogenolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta oxidation of fatty acids","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11219,"text":"The amine, histamine, is released from mast cells in the gastric mucosa. The secreted\r\nhistamine then acts through H2 receptors on oxyntic cells to cause the release of acid. What is this type of signaling known as?","explanation":"The described signaling, where the amine histamine is released from mast cells in the gastric mucosa and acts on H2 receptors of oxyntic cells to cause acid release, is known as **paracrine signaling**.\r\n\r\n In paracrine signaling, cells release signaling molecules (like histamine) into the extracellular fluid, which then act on nearby target cells possessing appropriate receptors (H2 receptors on oxyntic cells). The signaling molecule, histamine, acts locally and does not enter the bloodstream. This localized effect allows for precise control and regulation of cellular responses, such as acid secretion in the gastric mucosa.\r\n\r\n**Reference:**\r\n*Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology*, [Latest Edition]. Hall JE. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Autocrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paracrine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Exocrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apocrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endocrine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11220,"text":"Which of the following is a neuro-hormone?","explanation":"Vasopressin, also known as antidiuretic hormone (ADH), is a neuro-hormone produced by the hypothalamus and then stored and released from the posterior pituitary gland. It plays a vital role in **regulating water balance** and **osmolarity** in the body. When there is an increase in plasma osmolarity or a decrease in blood volume, the hypothalamus signals the release of vasopressin from the posterior pituitary. Vasopressin acts on the kidneys, promoting water reabsorption in the collecting ducts, and reducing water loss through urine, ultimately increasing blood volume and maintaining blood pressure.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasopressin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle stimulating hormone (FSH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone (LH)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11221,"text":"Which of the following is correct about the working of endocrine hormones?","explanation":"Endocrine hormones are **secreted by specialized cells** within endocrine glands or tissues into the bloodstream. From the bloodstream, these hormones travel throughout the body and interact with **target cells** possessing specific receptors for the respective hormone. Once the hormone binds to its receptor on the target cell's surface or within the cell, it triggers a cascade of cellular responses, regulating various physiological processes and maintaining homeostasis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 915.","responses":[{"text":"They are produced from one neuron and act on another","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are produced from one cell and act on another","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are produced from one artery and act on another","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are produced from one muscle and act on another","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11222,"text":"The differentiation between ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone)-dependent and ACTH-independent Cushing syndrome is made by administering high doses of which of the following synthetic glucocorticoids?","explanation":"The differentiation between **ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone)-dependent** and **ACTH-independent** Cushing syndrome is made by administering high doses of **dexamethasone**.\r\n\r\nDexamethasone is a potent synthetic glucocorticoid with a high affinity for glucocorticoid receptors. In the **high-dose dexamethasone suppression test**, administering a pharmacological dose of dexamethasone will suppress cortisol secretion in patients with **ACTH-dependent** Cushing syndrome, which is characterized by excessive ACTH production (e.g., pituitary adenoma or ectopic ACTH-secreting tumor). In contrast, patients with **ACTH-independent** Cushing syndrome (e.g., adrenal adenoma or carcinoma) will not show significant suppression of cortisol levels.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 170.","responses":[{"text":"Prednisolone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dexamethasone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylprednisolone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11224,"text":"What is the most important factor in the development of type-1 diabetes?","explanation":"The most crucial factor in the development of **Type 1 diabetes** is **genes**.\r\n\r\nThis form of diabetes is considered an autoimmune disease, wherein the immune system mistakenly attacks and destroys insulin-producing beta cells in the pancreas. While environmental factors may play a role in triggering the disease process, **genetic predisposition** is the fundamental factor driving the development of Type 1 diabetes. Certain genetic markers, such as **HLA-DQ and HLA-DR genes**, are strongly associated with an increased risk of developing this condition.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Genes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physical activity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Environment","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11226,"text":"What is the process of receiving sensory information and converting it to impulse for further processing called?","explanation":"The correct term for the process of **receiving sensory information and converting it into electrical impulses** for further processing is **signal transduction**.\r\n\r\nSignal transduction refers to the conversion of various forms of sensory stimuli (such as light, sound, touch, taste, and smell) into electrical signals or nerve impulses. This conversion is essential for the nervous system to process and interpret the sensory information effectively.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Retrieval","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Signal transduction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Encoding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Storage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11228,"text":"A doctor asks the patient to tense a group of muscles and then relax them. What is this technique called?","explanation":"The technique described where a patient is asked to **tense and then relax a group of muscles** is called **Progressive Relaxation**.\r\n\r\n Progressive Relaxation is a **behavioral technique** commonly used for stress reduction, relaxation, and management of anxiety. In this method, the patient is instructed to sequentially tense and then relax different muscle groups, promoting physical and mental relaxation. This practice helps individuals become more aware of bodily sensations, identify areas of tension, and learn how to release muscular and mental stress effectively.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aerobic exercise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep breathing exercise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progressive relaxation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aversion therapy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11229,"text":"Which of the following hormones has acute life-saving effects?","explanation":"Among the listed hormones, **aldosterone** exerts **acute life-saving effects** in response to certain physiological challenges.\r\n\r\nAldosterone, a mineralocorticoid hormone produced by the adrenal cortex, plays a crucial role in maintaining blood pressure and electrolyte balance. In acute situations, such as severe blood loss or dehydration, aldosterone secretion is rapidly increased. It acts on the **distal tubules and collecting ducts** of the kidneys, promoting **reabsorption of sodium** and **water retention** while excreting potassium and hydrogen ions. This process effectively **increases blood volume and blood pressure**, preventing further compromise and ensuring adequate perfusion to vital organs.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 958.","responses":[{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11230,"text":"Which of the following types of hormones are processed in the liver and their conjugated types are released in bile?","explanation":"Among the listed hormone types, **steroid hormones** are processed in the liver, and their **conjugated forms** are subsequently released in bile.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Steroid hormones","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tryptophan-derived hormones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptide hormones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tyrosine-derived hormones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11231,"text":"A 65-year-old woman comes into the outpatient department suffering from polyuria and polydipsia. She looks dehydrated and her skin has lost some turgor. Lab tests show glucosuria +4. What is the most important pathogenesis of this disease?","explanation":"In the presented case of a 65-year-old woman experiencing polyuria, polydipsia, dehydration, and glucosuria, the **most important pathogenesis** underlying her condition is **peripheral resistance** to insulin. This clinical scenario suggests the possibility of **Type 2 diabetes mellitus**.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucokinase gene mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HLA-DR4/ HLA-DR3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral resistance","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11232,"text":"Which serum prolactin level is used as a differential for macroprolactinoma diagnosis?","explanation":"A serum prolactin level \u003e5000 mlU/L is used as a differential criterion for diagnosing macroprolactinoma. Prolactinomas are pituitary adenomas that secrete excessive prolactin, leading to hyperprolactinemia. These tumors are categorized into microprolactinomas (\u003c10 mm) and macroprolactinomas (≥10 mm).","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"500-1000 mlU/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e5000 mlU/L","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e500 mlU/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003e10000 mlU/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1000-5000 mlU/L","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11233,"text":"Which of the following is the gold standard for diagnosing Helicobacter pylori?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Microbiological culture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Histopathology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea breath test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urease test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11972,"text":"Which of the following is the correct sequence of events for growth?","explanation":"The correct sequence of events for growth during puberty in females is **thelarche, adrenarche, growth spurt, and menarche**.\r\n\r\n1. **Thelarche**: Thelarche refers to the onset of breast development, and it is the first sign of puberty in females. It typically occurs around the age of 8 to 13 years.\r\n\r\n2. **Adrenarche**: Adrenarche is the maturation of the adrenal glands and the increased production of androgens (male sex hormones). This stage usually occurs between the ages of 8 and 14 years.\r\n\r\n3. **Growth Spurt**: The growth spurt is a rapid increase in height and weight that occurs during puberty. It is one of the most prominent signs of pubertal growth and usually occurs around the age of 9 to 14 years in females.\r\n\r\n4. **Menarche**: Menarche is the onset of the first menstrual period, indicating the ability to conceive. It occurs later in puberty, typically between the ages of 10 and 16 years.","reference":"Kenny LC, Bickerstaff H, eds. Gynaecology by Ten Teachers. 20th ed. CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group; 2017: 38.","responses":[{"text":"Menarche, adrenarche, thelarche, and growth spurt","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thelarche, adrenarche, growth spurt, and menarche","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth spurt, thelarche, adrenarche, and menarche","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thelarche, adrenarche, menarche, and growth spurt","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenarche, menarche, thelarche, and growth spurt","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12792,"text":"Which of the following is a life-threatening complication that may occur with improper management of diabetic ketoacidosis?","explanation":"While patients with DKA often present with an elevated serum potassium, they are typically potassium depleted. The acidosis present in DKA promotes the shift of potassium from the intracellular to the extracellular space. Improper management of DKA, especially aggressive insulin therapy without adequate potassium replacement, can cause a rapid shift of potassium into cells, leading to life-threatening hypokalemia. On the other hand, if a patient with DKA is not given insulin and fluids appropriately, the hyperkalemia can persist or worsen, leading to cardiac arrhythmias.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 738.","responses":[{"text":"Renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperkalemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral edema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14236,"text":"Which one of these is an autosomal recessive condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://rarediseases.org/rare-diseases/autoimmune-polyglandular-syndrome-type-1/#:~:text=APS%2D1%20is%20inherited%20in,usually%20will%20not%20show%20symptoms.","responses":[{"text":"MEN-2 syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurofibromatosis type 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MEN-1 syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Hippel-Lindau syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune polyglandular syndrome type I","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14895,"text":"A 58-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department for a general health checkup. Her blood pressure is 140/100 mm Hg, and her pulse rate is 89 per minute. The rest of her vitals are normal. She is 163 cm tall (5'4\") and weighs 102 kg (225 lbs). Her BMI is 38.4 kg/m². She mentions that she frequently wakes up from her sleep and her husband constantly complains about her snoring. \r\nThe physician advises her to lose weight for better health, but the patient complains that she has tried multiple times and follows the advice of her nutritionist religiously. She mentions she has heard of bariatric surgery and has been considering it for some time. \r\nThe physician advises trying medical therapy before moving on to surgical intervention. \r\n\r\nWhich of the following medications is usually prescribed to help weight loss only?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 765","responses":[{"text":"Sitagliptin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levothyroxine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metformin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orlistat","correct":true,"visible":false}]}
]

